<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Snow and sleet blanketed much of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Thursday and dozens of cars crashed on an icy mountain interstate, killing two people. The snow also blocked thousands of motorists on a coastal highway. Snow flurries appeared in the southern <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and sleet and rain fell around <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, including hills that were dry and ablaze only a week ago, as the storm swept from <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s midsection. As temperatures headed down to the 40s for the night, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> gave hotel vouchers to homeless people and opened shelters in a recreation center and an armory. Two armories opened as shelters in <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Ten crashes involving dozens of vehicles and two deaths occurred on Interstate 15 in <LOCATION> Cajon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON>. No information was immediately available on the deaths. At midmorning police began slowly escorting groups of cars through the pass behind snowplows rather than require use of chains, which causes miles of backup and hours of delay. `` It's just like a winter wonderland up there,'' said Officer <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Roden </PERSON>. Thousands of motorists were stuck when snow closed Highway 101 north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION>, which is about 150 miles north of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, police said. `` One of the problems is here we do n't have the snow equipment to take care of this _ it does n't happen here,'' said <ORGANIZATION> CHP </ORGANIZATION> Officer