<HEAD>Jazz on the Screen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's a moment in <PERSON> Clint </PERSON> <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON>'s movie, `` Bird,'' when the great jazzman <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> stands on a blackened <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> stage after finishing a concert, consuming massive doses of applause and sniffing a long-stemmed red rose. He was something of a god to jazz zealots, but perhaps the tortured musical genius never really got a chance to wake up and smell the roses. He mutilated his life with drugs and alcohol, and died at the age of 34 in 1955. <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON>, who has loved jazz since his childhood and who always wanted to film a portrait of <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, attempts to harness the Bird's creative spirit and all the creative juices of that time _ a time when bebop came to the fore and brought jazz into the modern age At the same time, it pokes into the underbelly of the jazz world with its stark portrayal of drugs, alcohol, debauchery. `` His life was obviously filled with many excesses _ sort of a dichotomy,'' <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON> says. `` How a person who can be so brilliant and who spent hours and hours to become as great as he did and have that kind of discipline could not in any other part of his life. That was always a wonder to me. `` But I wanted a movie where you root for him. ... I just wanted to explore the fact that he was brilliant and innovative, and the other just became a part of his life.'' <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON> even films `` Bird'' in a dark, brownish hue. `` Most of the jazz world is nocturnal,'' he says. `` TV unfortunately has shown a whole generation that flat light is the only way. I do n't like flat light. I like the feel of the movie; I like to look into a film instead of having it look out at you. I approached the color of it in terms of black and white.'' Forest <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> -LRB- `` Good Morning, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>,'' `` Platoon'' -RRB- is gentle yet fierce, playful yet obsessed in his role as <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, for which he was awarded the best actor prize at the <ORGANIZATION> Cannes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION>. It was well deserved for a stunning performance that even captures the hunched body stances once assumed by the musician as he performed. As <PERSON> Chan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Venora </PERSON> -LRB- `` Ironweed,'' `` F-X'' -RRB- finds the right balance between free spirit and strong, loving wife who battles her husband's philandering and personal demons and at the same time champions his work and well-being. `` Bird'' followed the success of last year's `` Round Midnight,'' the story of an expatriate sax player in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. Tenor saxophone great <PERSON> Dexter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, who once worked with <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, received an Academy Award nomination for his role as the tragic <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. Though based loosely on the late jazz musician <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Tavernier </PERSON>'s movie is a universal story of jazz artists who fled bigotry and rough times in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for the allure of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> during the 1940s,'50s and'60s. `` <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> Blues,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritt </PERSON>'s 1961 jazz movie starring <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Poitier </PERSON>, takes a more romantic, <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> approach. The late <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellington </PERSON> received an Oscar nomination for his score. In `` Bird,'' <PERSON> Lenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Niehaus </PERSON> did the score, which isolates <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s original playing of `` <PERSON> Laura </PERSON>,'' `` April in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>,'' `` Ornithology,'' `` <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s Mood'' and other jazz tunes and remixes his recorded solos with contemporary musicians including bassist <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, trumpeter <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Faddis </PERSON>, pianists <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> Jazz purists have been rankled by the soundtrack, which they say is technically excellent but misses the interplay between <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> and his sidemen. But <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON> defends his decision: `` If you're going to do a film and have stereophonic sound, you need to record well. <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> never had the opportunity to do stereophonic sound.'' <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, and took up first baritone and then alto sax while still in high school, which he left at the age of 14 so he could study such greats as <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> and <PERSON> Count </PERSON> <PERSON> Basie </PERSON> in the local clubs. He soon found himself in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where a young trumpet player named <PERSON> Dizzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> was all the rage. With Thelonious Monk and <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> on piano, <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> on drums and later a young <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> on trumpet, <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gillespie </PERSON> helped define and create a new musical venture in jazz _ bebop. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, whose nickname was Yardbird and shortened to <PERSON> Bird </PERSON>, stumbled into the lost world of night life. But even with the debiliation of drugs and alcohol, he never failed to solve musical problems and invent new directions. `` There have been no great harmonic changes in jazz since <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> and Dizzy,'' <PERSON> Eastwood </PERSON> says. And then he muses, what musical levels would <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> have reached today had he lived? `` It would be interesting,'' the actor-filmmaker says.
