<HEAD>Mother Sues City For $60 Million In Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city was hit with a $ 60 million lawsuit Wednesday alleging negligence on the part of Fire Department paramedics who did not treat a 9-year-old boy who eventually died from an asthma attack. Fire department spokesmen claim the ambulance was pelted with eggs and rocks and paramedics were forced to retreat when they arrived at a housing project Monday. `` All the evidence we have says there was nothing being thrown at the paramedics,'' attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bledsoe </PERSON> said. `` They just flatly refused to go up'' to the apartment. <PERSON> Bledsoe </PERSON> filed a lawsuit on behalf of <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarnagin </PERSON>, whose son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>, died. The lawsuit asks for $ 10 million in actual damages and $ 50 million in punitive damages. A city attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, said he was aware of the lawsuit but had no comment. The paramedics, summoned by an emergency call at 4:16 p.m. Monday, were not aware of the seriousness of the asthma attack when they first arrived at the housing project, the Fire Department says. They left the scene and returned 24 minutes later when police arrived, according to the Fire Department. Police officers said they found the boy in a bedroom in the family's fifth-floor apartment. He was taken to a hospital, where he was pronounced dead. Fire Department employees Tuesday washed the ambulance used by the paramedics, removing any trace of egg that may have been on it, <PERSON> Bledsoe </PERSON> said. `` When we heard about it we got a protective order barring anyone from doing anything to the ambulance until we could inspect it,'' he said The order was issued Wednesday by Cook County Judge <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>. Fire Department spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> said tapes of communications between the paramedics and dispatchers show proof that the ambulance was hit by flying objects. `` At all times paramedics and emergency medical technicians should avoid placing themselves in danger,'' <PERSON> Sheppard </PERSON> said, reading a city policy. The boy's mother and neighbors insist there was no danger to the paramedics.
