<HEAD>Last Five Italian Warships Leave Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The last five Italian warships have left the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> in the latest and largest cutback of foreign naval forces following the Iran-Iraq cease-fire, Italian officials say. The frigate Euro, flagship of the Italian flotilla, and the minehunters <PERSON> Castagno </PERSON> and Loto sailed through the Strait of Hormuz at the mouth of the gulf last week, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> said Wednesday. They were bound for home. The frigate Sagittario and the supply tanker <PERSON> Stromboli </PERSON> left Nov. 24 and reached their home port at the <LOCATION> Taranto </LOCATION> naval base in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> on Monday, the ministry said. Italian officials announced the withdrawal in early November, saying the Aug. 20 cease-fire, which halted fighting in the 8-year-old war, had brought a `` consolidation of stability'' to the strategic waterway. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> deployed warships in the gulf after the Italian container ship <PERSON> Jolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubino </PERSON> was attacked by Iranian gunboats while sailing to <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> on Sept. 2, 1987. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> kept up to eight ships in the gulf at once. The <PERSON> Jolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubino </PERSON> was the only Italian-flag vessel among more than 500 ships attacked by both sides during the four-year `` tanker war.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> regularly intercepted ships suspected of carrying war-related cargoes for <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> during the war. The Italian departure reduced the number of foreign warships in or near the gulf to about 50, with half belonging to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. At its peak late last year, the foreign naval force comprised more than 70 ships from seven countries.
