 Two derailed railroad cars leaking highly explosive liquid propane Wednesday forced the evacuation of about 100 residents and closed an interstate highway and rail routes in northern <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. A total of 26 cars derailed early Wednesday about 10 miles east of <LOCATION> Flagstaff </LOCATION> after 84 <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cars somehow became uncoupled during a stop, said a company official. Residents near the derailment were told at about 11 a.m. to plan to spend at least 24 hours away from their homes while authorities tried to defuse the cars leaking liquid propane. `` This has the potential to become a very dangerous situation,'' said <LOCATION> Coconino </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Richards </PERSON>. He said hazardous-materials teams from the <ORGANIZATION> Santa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> hoped to siphon off the propane through a makeshift rigging of pipes and valves and ignite it in a controlled burn. `` They ca n't offload it, because that would be too dangerous,'' <PERSON> Richards </PERSON> said. `` It's too dangerous to move heavy equipment in there because of the potential for an explosion.'' But later in the day, <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said that hazardous materials experts were considering an alternate strategy, an intricate process of pumping the propane out of the leaking propane cars with special equipment. The process would take up to 36 hours, he said. If it is used, the propane would be taken by truck and would be reloaded on different tank cars later, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. The experts hoped to decide on a stragegy by early Thursday, he said. The residents evacuated earlier Wednesday would not be allowed to return to their homes until the propane was completely removed. Authorities sealed off both the railroad right-of-way and Interstate 40 over the 58-mile stretch between <LOCATION> Flagstaff </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Winslow </LOCATION>. By late evening Wednesday, the road and railroad remained closed. State police helicopters also closed off the airspace over the wreckage, chasing away aircraft carrying photographers. An <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the derailment held up two trains. Two other cars carrying propane, one with a hazardous-cargo label, and 21 others derailed, but they were not leaking. The car with the hazardous-cargo label was believed to be carrying an industrial solvent, and was not considered explosive, officials said. <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fe </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the train was parked at the <ORGANIZATION> Ralston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Purina </ORGANIZATION> pet-food plant in East Flagstaff to drop off one car when the cars became uncoupled and began rolling east down a slight grade. The runaway reached an estimated 40 mph before the cars derailed on a curve. No one was injured, he said. Investigators began a probe to determine why the train sections became separated, but the cause was not immediately determined, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. The westbound train originated in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.
