<HEAD>PLO Decision Raises Problems for Israel, Questions About Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sudden <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> raises tough political problems for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and suggests disarray within the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in its final weeks. Even while Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and other senior officials were making preparations at the White House for Wednesday's historic announcement, President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was criticizing the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> for failing to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions for a dialogue. Speaking at the Executive Office Building just across the street, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> vowed to continue the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's tough stand against <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s organization. He demanded `` a clear and unambiguous statement'' explicitly recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, renouncing terrorism and accepting two major <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolutions on the right of all states to live within secure boundaries. `` Before we have a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> the signals have to be clear, unmistakable, unambiguous,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, biting off each word with decisive crispness. Simultaneously, however, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was giving a news conference in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> seized on as evidence that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman had come around to accepting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions. The result was announcements by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and by <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> that there would be a `` substantive dialogue'' with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> _ leaving <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> looking like the odd man out. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, meanwhile, did not explain later at a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> news conference how what <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said on Wednesday had differed from what the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader had said a day earlier. The day-earlier comments had been declared unacceptable. Having denied <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> a visa less than three weeks earlier, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> suddenly was approving direct dealings with a man he had denounced as an `` accessory'' in acts of terrorism against Israelis and Americans. Asked what was different about <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s most recent statement, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said cryptically: `` It was clear. It was not encumbered.'' The decision was in a long <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> tradition of policy shifts that always are defended as not policy shifts at all. It clearly backs <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> into a corner, now standing alone in shunning the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he would not presume to advise another country what it ought to do. `` It's totally for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to make its own decisions about what it wants to do, and there's nothing to be inferred judgmentally about what they should do,'' he said. The choice <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> faces is to watch the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, its closest friend, make arrangements for <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and not participate, or to agree to attend a peace conference with the participation of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> now a virtual certainty. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> could come under pressure, too _ from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to make good on <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s declaration renouncing terrorism in all forms. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, undoubtedly, will be asked by reporters in the next few days why he seemed so out of step with what was brewing within the White House. In a way, though, he may benefit from the decision taken by the outgoing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Any political storm caused by embracing the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> will not fall on him. It's a decision that may have been inevitable, and one he now will not have to make. But he may have to make one just as tough _ whether to support a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he was not endorsing statehood for the Palestinians by approving the dialogue. And yet, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s demand for a state carved out of Israeli-held territory will be bolstered by its entry into <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s diplomatic community.
</TEXT>
