<HEAD>U.S. Wheat Group Disputes Crop Projection By International Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> is forecasting that world wheat production could rise to a record level in the 1989-90 season and start a modest rebuilding of depleted grain stockpiles. But an official of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> says the council's assertion is premature and that i's too early to make such projections. The council said Wednesday that wheat production could reach a record 550 million metric tons in the 1989-90 season. That would be 5 million tons more than is expected to be consumed and would allow world stocks to rebuild, said the council. A decline in stocks after the estimated fall of 37 million tons this season would leave an `` uncomfortably narrow margin of security between world supply and demand,'' the council said. If the council is correct about 1989-90 wheat production exceeding use once again and starting another buildup in surpluses, it could mean downward pressure on wheat prices. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has not made any such projections yet. `` Our tendency over time is to have more faith in the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> projections,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwensen </PERSON>, the association's executive vice president here. `` The wheat council projections have a constituency of developing countries that they inform through their various forecasts.'' <PERSON> Schwensen </PERSON> added in a telephone interview: `` Whether it exceeds -LRB- consumption -RRB- or not, I think it's heroic to make any predictions about that at this point.'' Stockpiles built up during the wheat glut of the mid-1980s are being depleted this season because of the sharp drop in 1988-89 wheat production caused by droughts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. World wheat production for 1988-89 now is forecast by the council at 500 million tons, 13 million tons below the previous season's figure and 37 million down on the 1986-87 record Tighter supplies this season have led to higher world prices which are encouraging growers to increase plantings for 1989-90, the council said. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has forecast global wheat production this season at 502.5 million tons, about in line with the council's estimate for 1988-89. But <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has not yet projected world wheat output for 1989-90. But department officials have been saying that the recent higher prices and draw-down of wheat stocks are expected to boost plantings for next season.
