<HEAD>Trial To Offer Rare Inside Look At Roman Catholic Church</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The trial of a <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> priest's claim that <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> violated his academic freedom will provide an unusual look at the church's inner workings. The suit was brought by the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> after the university revoked his right to teach theology on grounds that his writings were at odds with the faith. The suit pits <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s claims of academic freedom against the church's contention it has the power to discipline clergy who stray from the orthodox teachings of the faith. Cardinal <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and chancellor of the university, was the first witness as the trial got under way Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. Cardinal <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardin </PERSON>, archbishop of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> who chaired the university's board of trustees when action was first taken against <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, is also set to testify. <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> defended the university's decision to revoke <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s `` canonical mission'' to teach <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> theology after <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> authorities determined his writings were at odds with the faith <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, 54, refused an offer to teach ethics outside the university's religious department. The university contends that it was merely enforcing the highest authority of the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, which had revoked <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s right to teach Roman Catholic theology. As an ordained priest, the university contends, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> has an obligation to obey the revocation of his mission to teach <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> theology. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> contends he was never conferred such authority and his contract to teach was no different than any other university professor with tenure. <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> defended the decision to discipline <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>, saying: `` the case of Father <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> had become a widely known matter. It has caused, in my opinion, a great deal of harm to the church.'' The church has the power to declare that a theologian no longer speaks for the faith `` when it believes a theologian has seriously departed from the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> teaching,'' <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> said. An investigation of <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s writings, which, among other things, disputed the church's stance on birth control and homosexuality, determined he was `` unfaithful to the role as professor of theology,'' <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> said. Because of the case's notoriety, it was important that he be removed from the theology, particularly because of the university's `` unique relationship both with the Holy See and the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in this country,'' <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> said Founded in 1885 by Pope <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> XIII </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> functions as one of few `` pontifical universities'' in the country that is governed directly by the church. The action was taken because `` it seemed inconceivable to the board of trustees of the university that we could simply join in defiance on the part of Father <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> testified. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, said the decision to remove <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> from the ecclesiastical faculty violated academic freedoms specifically conferred on the faculty following a strike over the issue in 1967. Moreover, <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> said <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s dissenting views, summarized in his work `` Faithful Dissent,'' were well known to the church long before his dismissal earlier this year. `` The actions that have been taken against him are not because of some brand-new heretical position,'' <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> said. `` If the notion of academic freedom in the specific context of the present case means anything, it means the university guaranteed a freedom in the face of public dissent from certain church teachings,'' <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON> said in pre-trial arguments. But <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baine </PERSON>, who represents the university, said the court had no right to question the church's application of canon law, which governed the relationship between <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> and the university. `` Father <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> thinks he has n't an obligation to his church to abide by this declaration,'' <PERSON> Bain </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> was trying to change the university into something that he `` wants it to be,'' <PERSON> Baine </PERSON> argued. Judge <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisberg </PERSON> agreed that the court has no power to second-guess application of church law, but ruled that the issue in the case is whether these canons formed the basis of <PERSON> Curran </PERSON>'s contract <PERSON> Hickey </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> was implicitly conferred a `` canonical mission'' when he was hired. Following his suspension from <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1987, <PERSON> Curran </PERSON> was a visiting professor at <LOCATION> Cornell </LOCATION>. He currently has a one-year appointment at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <