<FIRST>r w PM-HomeEquityLoans     12-15 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Equity Loans,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Borrowers Wary Of Foreclosure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A survey on home equity loans found most borrowers aware they could face foreclosure if the money is n't repaid, but a consumer group said many people still do n't know what they're getting into when they borrow against their homes The Survey Research Center at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that 58 percent of homeowners had a first mortgage, and 11 percent had other loans secured by their equity, or the value of the home beyond what is owed on it. The July-November survey of 2,510 households found that traditional second mortgages _ loans for a fixed amount to be repaid on a fixed schedule _ were held by 5 percent of the homeowners. The newer home equity lines of credit, which allow people to borrow money at their discretion up to an approved credit limit, were held by 6 percent. Eighty-four percent of the homeowners with loans secured by their equity listed foreclosure as a risk should they be unable to repay the money, and another 6 percent to 7 percent mentioned other legal actions as a possibility, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON>, director of the university's Surveys of Consumers. `` Their caution in using their home equity line of credit ... comes out of this understanding of the consequences of missing payments,'' he said. Among families with approved lines of credit, 31 percent had not borrowed any money, either because the planned need for the money had not arisen or because the credit line was meant to serve as a cash reserve in case of emergency, according to the survey. Among those who had borrowed against their lines of credit, the median outstanding debt was just 10 percent of net home equity, although the median amount the families had authorization to borrow was 32 percent of net equity. `` They're well aware that they're betting their home and they're very cautious about it,'' <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> said Some consumer groups have criticized banks for advertising low rates on home equity loans that are available only for a short period and for failing to disclose important information about conditions and fees on the loans. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Meier </PERSON> of the private <ORGANIZATION> Consumers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said `` the suggestion that consumers generally know the risks they are assuming is not justified'' by the survey's findings. `` We think there are a lot of problems,'' she said. Even consumers who are aware of the risk of foreclosure may be surprised by changing repayment plans, rising interest rates and other conditions that could make it more difficult to repay their loans, she said. The <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> survey was supported by 35 corporations, financial institutions and trade associations with an interest in home equity loans. <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> discussed the results at a news conference sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, two of the groups that helped finance the survey.
