<SECOND>PM-Making The Decision,740</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Arafat Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Decision Caps Diplomatic Ping-Pong Over PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s decision to open direct talks with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> capped a month of intense debate over recent <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> overtures, a period in which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> stood virtually alone in the court of world opinion. The historic decision announced Wednesday came 18 days after Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> refused to allow <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to enter the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was kept out because his organization `` engaged in terrorism against Americans and others.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made clear Wednesday that he was not forgiving the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> for its past but said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statements earlier in the day recognizing the existence of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and renouncing terrorism had met standards set in 1975 for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. Many nations attacked <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s Nov. 26 decision not to allow <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to come to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made the decision just 11 days after the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s governing body, had accepted U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338 as the basis for peace talks and world leaders were eager for <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to elaborate. The criticism of <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> came from all quarters and included assertions the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was violating the agreement under which <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> serves as the organization's headquarters. Even Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, without specifically referring to the decision, said `` every obstacle'' to the peace process should be removed. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> delegates passed a resolution denouncing the decision, and only the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> voted against it. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> abstained. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stood by <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> then took the unprecedented step of moving its debate to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, where on Tuesday <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> made his long-awaited speech and declared, `` Come, let us make peace.'' He recognized <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, condemned terrorism and said peace negotiations should be based on Resolutions 242 and 338 _ the three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions for opening a dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had received advance word <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> might meet the standards and had, according to sources, informed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> that he was prepared to announce that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was ready to talk to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. But, after a close examination of the speech, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s language was ambiguous and `` did not meet our conditions.'' <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> then called a Wednesday news conference in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and, carefully choosing his words as advisers whispered to him, read a statement that called for a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state to co-exist alongside <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, said resolutions 242 and 338 should serve as the framework for peace talks and that `` we totally and absolutely renounce all forms of terrorism, including individual terrorism, group and state terrorism.'' At virtually the same time <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> spoke, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was applauding the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader's Tuesday speech but repeating the standard <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration line that it had not gone far enough. `` I want it clear, I want it unambiguous, I want is so nobody can argue with what's been said,'' said the president-elect, apparently unaware of the clearer statements just made by <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. But at the White House and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, where again advance word had been received that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was ready to meet the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions, the day was spent determining whether he had. At 9:30 a.m. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was briefed by Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, his national security adviser, and told <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> planned a news conference at which he might use the `` right language.'' Four hours later <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chief of staff <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Duberstein </PERSON> and reaffirmed that he was ready to authorize dialogue provided <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> met the conditions, according to <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides. At 4 p.m. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> spoke again: <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had a copy of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statement and indicated <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> had met the conditions. Less than a half-hour passed when <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> briefed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and gave him a copy of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s statement. At 5:12 p.m., according to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Duberstein </PERSON> called <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and told him they believed <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> had met the conditions. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> immediately authorized the dialogue. The administration notified <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and others of the decision. Even before <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made the formal announcement, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> issued a statement saying it regretted the move. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made it official just after 6:30 p.m. `` I did n't change my mind,'' he said in response to the inevitable question. `` They made their statements clear.''
