<HEAD>Arafat, From Guerrilla Chieftain To Statesman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has come a long way from a guerrilla commando force leader to a statesman. He is the symbol of Palestinians' desire for a homeland, never wavering in his dream of creating a Palestinian state. For nearly three decades the 59-year-old <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has been both revolutionary chieftain and politician, ricocheting between touching the dream and losing control of the movement to rivals backed by other Arab governments. Each setback of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> _ chased from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> in 1970 and from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1982 _ was trumpeted as the final demise of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. Each time, he returned. And this month he piloted the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> through making the concessions demanded by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> before it would open a dialogue. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has denounced him for years as the archterrorist masterminding attempts to destroy the Jewish state. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> just last month denied him a visa to address the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, citing his links to terrorism. But the base of his success has been widespread support among the world's 5.5 million Palestinians. In the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, his pictures sprout among demonstrators in the year-old uprising against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> seems consumed by his mission for a homeland. He does not smoke or drink, and is notorious for late-night meetings. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, without wife, children or fixed address, says he married the cause when he formed an underground <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> movement, <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>, in October 1959. His date and place of birth have never been confirmed, though the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> does not dispute the version that he was born Aug. 29, 1929, in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Born <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Abed </PERSON> Ar ` ouf <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, his father came from a prosperous merchant On his mother's side he can trace his ancestry back to <PERSON> Fatima </PERSON>, daughter of the Moslem prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> says he smuggled arms to Arab forces during the 1948 Arab-Israeli war, then went to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> to enroll in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> University. In 1952, he was elected president of the Palestinian student union in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in 1957 after taking part in the Suez War as a reserve officer in the Egyptian army. He worked in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> as a government engineer before forming his own successful contracting firm. The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> was created in 1964, and <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> brought <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> above ground on Jan. 1, 1965 with its first military commando operation against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> led commando operations against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> before the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. Later, he traveled clandestinely through the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> to organize <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> military units. He was elected <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman in 1969. In 1970, he faced his first serious challenge from an Arab government. <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, threatened by the growing power of the Palestinians within his kingdom, moved his army against them. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> escaped one of two acknowledged assassination attempts that year; the second came in October 1971 on an inspection tour in <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. He says he never sleeps in the same place for two nights running. In 1974, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> granted the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> observer status. An enduring image of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is when he addressed the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> offering an olive branch of peace but wearing an empty holster. In the late 1970s, his guerrillas became embroiled in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s civil war Their strength in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> led <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to invade in 1982. Palestinian guerrillas were scattered from <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> after world governments intervened to lift an Israeli siege of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. Guerrilla leaders, disgusted with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s loyalty to commanders who did not stand and fight the Israelis, got Syrian backing to try to unseat him. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was expelled from <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> in June 1983. Pro-Arafat forces were evacuated from <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, that December. But <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> moved <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters to <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> and gradually rebuilt a consensus among Palestinian groups. That consensus _ glued together with the uprising in the occupied territories _ led to this month's announced change in the Palestinian position and the projected dialogue with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> made a political drive in the last month to convince the world they are peaceful, moderate, and worthy of representing Palestinians in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process.
