<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Postal Worker Holed Up In New Orleans Post Office After Shooting
Three</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs with gunman located, at least one hostage
being held; negotiations being conducted; picks up 5th graf pvs,
`Authorities identified ...' SUBS 14th-15th grafs pvs, `Ayers said
...' with 1 graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A postal employee pulled a shotgun out at the main post office Wednesday night, wounded three people and holed up in the building with at least one hostage, authorities said. The gunman eluded police for about five hours before agents found him in a room used for coffe breaks during a room-to-room search of the block-wide building, said <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Volney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>. The gunman, who <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said was holding at least one hostage, fired two shots at agents, who then backed off. `` He was barricaded behind a door. As the agents approached he fired,'' said <PERSON> Cesta </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON>, a post office spokesman. Negotiations with the gunman were being conducted by telephone, <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> said early Thursday. Earlier, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said, the gunman got into an argument with a co-worker and pulled a weapon out of a bag. Authorities identified the gunman as <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, about 40, a six-year postal worker. One of the people shot was the person <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> argued with, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said. He did not identify the victim or elaborate. `` I was going to mail this box of stuff I have and the security guard came down. He was real excited,'' said a witness, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Wingerter </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. `` The guard was screaming, ` There's a guy with a gun!''' Four hours after the incident began at 8:30 p.m., authorities said an undetermined number of postal employees were apparently still inside the building but it was not known if they were being held hostage. About midnight, a dozen postal employees who had been laying low on the vast second floor escaped through a back door, <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said, leaving about 20 to 30 or the 500 workers on the night shift unaccounted for. `` We still think he's in there,'' he said. `` Some postal inspectors have evacuated. ... They were n't really hostages.'' <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON> said the workers who escaped had seen <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> but had n't had any contact with him. The employees were hustled away by <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> after they came out of the building. <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> may have had marital problems. `` The information we have at this time ... is that his wife did leave him and left the city. We have not talked to him, but that is the rumor we have at this time,'' <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> said. Two patients were at <ORGANIZATION> Tulane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> where they were in stable condition, a <ORGANIZATION> Tulane </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. One person was hit in the thigh and one in the arm. A third person was wounded in the eye and was undergoing surgery late Wednesday at <ORGANIZATION> Charity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, a hospital spokeswoman said. `` I do n't think anybody is hurt real bad at the present time,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> McSwain </PERSON>, police surgeon. `` I know nobody has any life-threatening injuries.'' <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> said unidentified relatives were at the scene to assist with negotiations. There was no word if <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> was demanding anything, said <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, whose agency was in charge of the situation because the post office is federal property. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Vale </PERSON>, a postal worker who was working on the ground floor, said, `` I just saw some people come running from upstairs, saying there was a man loose with a shotgun.'' A security guard told police that the gunman might be hiding on the second floor where letter-sorting machines and other large equipment is located. `` There's plenty of places to hide up there,'' <PERSON> Vale </PERSON> said. Special police teams dressed in flak jackets surrounded the post office on <LOCATION> Loyola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> on the edge of the central business district. <PERSON> Wingerter </PERSON> said the security guard ran to the door to make sure the half dozen or so postal workers and customers in the immediate area escaped out the front safely. `` I heard one shot and then the people started coming out,'' he said. `` Even after the shot, there were people driving up mailing letters for about five minutes. It was crazy.'' Adding to the confusion, holiday shoppers poured out the adjacent <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> department store to see what was going on. On Aug. 20, 1986, part-time mailman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> walked into the post office in <LOCATION> Edmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION>, with guns and ammunition hidden in his mail bag and began shooting. He fatally wounded 14 postal workers and injured six others before killing himself. Police, thinking <PERSON> Sherrill </PERSON> was holding workers hostage, waited outside for an hour before entering the building to aid the wounded and to free employees who had hidden from the gunman. Witnesses said the final shots were heard about 40 minutes before police entered the building.
