<HEAD>Many U.S. Jews Cautiously Support PLO Move; Arab-Americans Endorse
It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Arafat, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jewish groups warily supported the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's historic decision to sit down with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, while Arab-Americans said the policy reversal rekindled hope for <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace. Several American Jewish leaders said they trusted President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> in their decision to open a `` substantive dialogue'' with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, but called on <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to back his words of peace with action. `` We understand that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, having set standards for speaking with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> having met those minimum standards, that it is appropriate for us to live up to its commitment,'' said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON>, national director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It is a first step. Now we must watch to see if the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> will match words with deeds.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zogby </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab-American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, called the government's decision to end its longtime rejection of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> as a party to <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace efforts an `` important step forward.'' `` The dialogue should throw into sharp relief the failure of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to say yes to the very issues that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> has now acceded to,'' <PERSON> Zogby </PERSON> said. `` Our hope is that the dialogue is productive and that peace is now possible.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, legislators from both parties cautiously endorsed the move. `` It may be a blind alley, but an alley worth treading with eyes open,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugar </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>. `` This dialogue in no way mitigates our steadfast support of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. But I hope <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will at least be willing to informally acknowledge this process as a worthy attempt.'' `` In the interest of peace and security for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and all parties in the region, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has no sensible choice but to begin a dialogue,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> foreign operations appropriations subcommittee But, he added, `` the proof will still lie in deeds and not words.'' <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who nearly a decade ago was forced by then-President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> to resign as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> for meeting with a <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> representative, applauded the decision, saying, `` People were not ready for this before now.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said Wednesday he authorized the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to enter into `` a substantive dialogue'' with the Palestinian group after <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> said he was renouncing `` all forms of terrorism.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, who only two weeks ago barred <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> from entering the <LOCATION> Uni