<HEAD>Woman Gives Birth Alone With Help of 911 Dispatcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOND DU LAC, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Candy <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> was alone when she gave birth to a healthy baby girl, whose deliver got a `` long-distance'' boost by a 911 police communciations officer. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, 26, called the emergency number early Tuesday and was on the line with Officer <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> for about 10 minutes before giving birth to her full-term daughter. Paramedics arrived moments later. `` I'm having my baby _ I'm at home,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> told <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said she was alone, but that her parents were on their way to her apartment, according to a tape of the call. An ambulance was dispatched, and <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON> told <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> to stay on the telephone line. She then calmed the pregnant woman as <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> screamed with each contraction. The delivery went just fine, said a paramedic who took the mother and daughter to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Agnes </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>.
