<HEAD>Arafat's Political Triumph Could Trigger Radical Backlash</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to talk to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is a major political triumph for <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> that could breathe new life into the comatose <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process _ or touch off a violent backlash by Palestinian radicals. There is also the possibility that factions outside the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> such as the one led by terrorist mastermind <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> may simply unleash a new wave of terror to wreck the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman's diplomatic initiative. If the breakthrough fails to produce solid political gains, particularly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to negotiate, it could trigger attacks by radicals within the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> who fear <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has made too many concessions in the Palestinians' 40-year-old struggle for a homeland. The <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, which reconciled with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> last year after a four-year split, has already accused him of `` capitulation'' by renouncing terrorism and recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. Col. <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON>, who leads the Syrian-based breakaway Fatah-Uprising faction, on Wednesday branded <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> `` a traitor ... for his surrenderist concessions to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> enemy.'' <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON>, known by his nom de guerre of <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON>, split from the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 with other dissident factions in a Syrian-backed mutiny launched to protest <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s moves toward moderation. After fierce fighting, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> and his loyalists, already forced out of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 1982 invasion, were driven out of their last Lebanese stronghold. Capt. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON>, commander of the extremist Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, declared angrily in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> Wednesday night: `` <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has recognized and offered four-fifths of the Palestinian land to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leadership has accepted that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is there to stay and seeks a Palestinian homeland only in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, abandoning the dream of regaining all of pre-1948 Palestine. `` By renouncing violence and terrorism, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is condemning anyone who uses the gun against the Israeli occupier,'' <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has offered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> what he does n't have. The land of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> is not the property of any organization or any individual.'' West German authorities six weeks ago arrested 13 suspected <ORGANIZATION> PFLP-GC </ORGANIZATION> members who they said were planning terrorist attacks. They also seized explosives. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> and his top lieutenants would be targets along with Israelis and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> if the radicals go on the warpath again. For 15 years, since he first showed signs of moderation, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has had to battle not only the Israelis, but Palestinian extremists and hard-line <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states led by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, whose President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> has long sought to wrestle control of the Palestinian cause from <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>. Gunmen led by the renegade <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>, wanted by a dozen countries, have assassinated a score of key <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> aides over the years in a campaign to silence the moderates. Others have been killed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s secret service, <LOCATION> Mossad </LOCATION>. The Israelis' latest victim was <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s right-hand man, <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Wazir </PERSON>, who was slain in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION> on April 16. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration agreed Wednesday to open direct talks with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> after he told a special <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> session in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> renounces `` all forms of terrorism'' and said it explicitly recognizes <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. That was an abrupt turnaround by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which only the day before had said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> had not gone far enough to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions for a dialogue. Last month, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> steered the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s parliament-in-exile and highest decision-making body, to implicitly recognize <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist by accepting <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338. It also declared an independent Palestinian state in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, where Palestinians have been in revolt for a year. Radical <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> factions disagreed with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s moderate strategy, which was primarily aimed at persuading the Americans to deal directly with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and put pressure on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to negotiate. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, the prime mover behind the wave of airliner hijackings of the 1960s and 1970s, and the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> nonethless reluctantly went along with the <ORGANIZATION> PNC </ORGANIZATION> declaration `` in the interest of unity.'' But <PERSON> Habash </PERSON> warned <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> last month: `` We're backing your efforts because this is what the majority wants. But we do n't believe moderation will pay. `` We ca n't wait forever. If you fail, you have to come back to this council to say so and we can then decide the future course.''
