<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSDrug     12-15 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Drug,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: AZT Reverses Mental Impairment of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The AIDS drug AZT can improve memory and attention and ease other mental problems that are frequent symptoms of AIDS, a study published today shows. HIV, the AIDS virus, attacks the brain as well as the body's immune system Mental lapses can be the first signs of the disease. The latest study, published in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, confirms earlier reports showing that AZT can relieve these mental symptoms, at least in their first stages. The drug, also known as zidovudine and Retrovir, is the only medicine approved for AIDS treatment. While it does not cure AIDS, AZT relieves victims' physical symptoms and prolongs their lives. The latest work, directed by Dr. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmitt </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, was part of a larger study of the drug's overall safety and effectiveness. Of 262 patients who participated, nearly half were found to have some neurologic impairment when the study started. Sixty of these people were randomly chosen to take AZT, while 69 got placebos. Two months after treatment started, those who got AZT scored significantly better on tests of attention, memory, motor skills and general mental speed. People with full-blown AIDS improved more than those who had the pre-AIDS disease called AIDS-related complex, or ARC. `` These data are also important because they show that the neurologic dysfunction caused by HIV infection may be reversible to some extent,'' the researchers wrote.
</TEXT>
