<FIRST>r a PM-CancerTests     12-15 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cancer Tests,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rodent Tests Poor Way to Evaluate Chemicals for Cancer Risk, Study
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lengthy testing in rats and mice to predict whether a chemical poses a cancer hazard in humans usually fails to provide enough information to justify its cost, researchers asserted today. Most chemicals should be classified instead on the basis of short-term lab tests, says a cost-benefit analysis in the British journal Nature. Concerns over rodent testing have been raised before, centering on the uncertainty over how relevant they are for predicting how a chemical will affect people. The researchers said 30 percent of chemicals tested for cancer-causing potential in one program behaved differently in rats than in mice. Rodent tests are probably no more predictive for humans and could be much less, since people are more biologically different from rodents than rats are from mice, researchers said. Before deciding on whether to use a long-term rodent test, regulators should consider results of short-term testing and the costs to society of misclassifying a chemical, researchers said. For most chemicals, proceeding to the rodent tests would not be worth the cost, they said. Social costs of misclassifying a chemical include additional cancers if a dangerous chemical is wrongly labeled safe. If a safe chemical is erroneously labeled cancer-causing, society loses access to a potentially valuable compound or pays for needless precautions. The researchers are from <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie-Mellon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
