<HEAD>Man Accused In Second Rape; Held on $20,000 Bond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An unemployed truck driver is accused of raping two women in separate assaults along the same densely wooded stretch of highway where the bodies of six women have been discovered since July, officials said. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges he abducted and raped a woman at knifepoint in August 1987. He was held at the <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> jail on $ 20,000 bond. Afterward, a second woman who identified <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> in a composite photograph accused him of raping her in July, said <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pina </PERSON>. `` The two rape cases have come out as a legitimate result of this investigation'' into the highway serial killings, said <PERSON> Pina </PERSON>, although he declined to confirm news reports that <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> is a suspect in the slayings. `` There's a good list of suspects we have. They're all being checked out,'' <PERSON> Pina </PERSON> said at a news conference Wednesday. `` I think we are definitely closing in. The circle is becoming smaller and smaller.'' The partially clad skeletons of six women have been found since July in a six - to eight-mile radius along Interstate 195 and Route 140 in <LOCATION> Dartmouth </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Freetown </LOCATION> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibney </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Pina </ORGANIZATION>, declined to say whether <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a divorced father of two who lives with his mother and grandmother, had been among those questioned in the slayings. <PERSON> Pina </PERSON> has said he believes the six killings were likely the victims of the same killer or killers and that the victims all had ties to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Weld </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> neighborhood, known for prostitution and drugs. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubelaker </PERSON>, a forensic pathologist with the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> called in to examine the victims' remains, said all six women apparently died in a similar manner, but he declined to detail his findings. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, who has also worked as a welder and lives about 10 blocks from the <LOCATION> Weld </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> area, was arrested at home Tuesday. He was charged with aggravated rape, kidnapping, and assault and battery with a dangerous weapon. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, the public defender representing <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, said his client `` has been charged with only one crime. I think that to try to link that to any other events is very unfair.'' <PERSON> Gibney </PERSON> said an arraignment on the second rape charge would not be held unless <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> posted bail. `` At that time we would slap the other warrant on him, but barring that he's just going to sit there -LRB- in jail -RRB- until he goes before the grand jury on the other charges,'' he said. Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> scheduled a pretrial hearing on Dec. 21 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> also will appear at that time on charges of assault and battery with a deadly weapon in an unrelated fight, <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON> said.
