<HEAD>Four People Accused of Election Law Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four businessman face up to 17 years in prison if convicted on charges they tried to illegally aid Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>'s campaign by funneling money to an opponent of his chief rival. The five-count federal indictment handed up Wednesday contends that $ 120,000 was used for an advertising campaign in support of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> candidate <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Vallen </PERSON>, who ran against <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., and Republican Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zschau </PERSON> in 1986 `` We were not involved in any way, even indirectly,'' <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> <PERSON> Flanders </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. According to acting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Feess </PERSON>, the defendants solicited some 55 contributors to write checks to <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stripe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION>, which produced a TV ad for <ORGANIZATION> Vallen </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Feess </PERSON> told a news conference that the people who wrote checks were reimbursed for amounts running from $ 1,000 to $ 4,000. He declined to say whether the check writers knew they were violating election laws. `` The individuals were told different things by different people,'' <PERSON> Feess </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Feess </PERSON> stressed that <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> knew nothing about the plan and had no role in approving it. There was also no evidence that anyone on <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>'s staff was involved. `` We have absolutely no evidence that Senator <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> knew or approved of this action,'' he said, adding there is no indication that it had any influence on the outcome of the election. <PERSON> Cranston