<HEAD>Oscar-Winning Epic Restored For Re-Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-six years after the premiere of `` Lawrence of Arabia,'' the Oscar-winning epic will be re-released with scenes that had been cut from the original and a new look and sound created by a $ 600,000 restoration. The re-edited `` Lawrence'' will be just as its director, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON>, intended. `` ` Lawrence of Arabia' was the first film I saw that made me want to be a moviemaker,'' said director <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>, a co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> and Video Preservation. The film institute and <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> announced the re-release on Wednesday. The center will receive proceeds from a series of benefits at which the restored film will premiere: Feb. 4 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, Feb. 5 in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and Feb. 12 in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The 2 -LCB- years of work done on `` Lawrence of Arabia'' were `` the most expensive, extensive and difficult film restoration ever attempted,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, an archivist who conducted the restoration for the institute. `` Lawrence of Arabia'' won Academy Awards for best picture, director, color cinematography, color art direction, sound, editing and music, but <PERSON> Lean </PERSON>'s original editing plan was not followed in the rush to get the movie ready in 1962. Lean, 80, rerecorded lost parts of the original sound track with <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Toole </PERSON>, who starred as T.E. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Guinness </PERSON>, who played King <PERSON> Faisal </PERSON>. New lines were added. Missing ones were redubbed. `` All of their voices have mellowed,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said, `` and so we had to change the harmonics by using computers.'' Existing prints of the film were in terrible shape, said <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. She and filmmaker <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scorsese </PERSON> are chairmen of the institute's film-preservation fund. `` Parts of the film had been cut and lost, and the color was appalling,'' <PERSON> Steel </PERSON> said. `` But now the film looks brand new. The color is perfect, and it's the cut that <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON> wanted.''
