<HEAD>Roman Catholic Order Expels Activist Priest in Haiti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> order said today it had expelled an activist priest in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> it accused of instigating violence and exalting class warfare. The priest was the apparent target of a September attack that killed 13 people. The Rev. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertrand </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> had been at odds with superiors of his <ORGANIZATION> Salesian </ORGANIZATION> order in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> for some time. He had been ordered to leave his homeland and go to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> by Oct. 17. But <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, 35, defied the order and a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Salesian </ORGANIZATION> order, the Rev. <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON>, said he is still on the island. A communique by the <ORGANIZATION> Salesian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> said <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> has rebuffed repeated attempts to correct his behavior, which they described as `` in contrast with his <ORGANIZATION> Salesian </ORGANIZATION> and priestly vocation.'' `` The type of political commitment he has assumed is in serious contrast with the clear will of the founder -LRB- of the order -RRB-. In addition, the incitement to hate and violence, the exaltation of class struggle, go directly against that fidelity to the -LRB- teaching -RRB- of the church that forms a living part of the Salesian spirit.'' It called him a `` destabilizing'' element for Haitian Roman Catholics. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> has led calls for an uprooting of the vestiges of the former regime of <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON>, who was overthrown in 1986. In September, <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> was the apparent object of a bloody attack on his church in the Haitian capital of <LOCATION> Port-au-Prince </LOCATION> during a Sunday Mass by thugs linked to the ousted regime. Thirteen people were killed and more than 70 were wounded. <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> escaped. The massacre provoked another military coup, in which rank-and-file soldiers ousted Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> and replaced him with Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Prosper </PERSON> <PERSON> Avril </PERSON>. The statement said the action by the order was `` painful'' but that there was no way <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON> could remain a <LOCATION> Salesian </LOCATION> without changing his ways. `` The Salesians continue to pray for <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>, still nourishing the hope of a sincere fraternal embrace as soon as he wants it,'' the statement said. The order's spokesman said the decree, which was ratified by the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> last week, did not change <PERSON> Aristide </PERSON>'s status as a priest.
