 The state treasurer has asked the federal government to investigate an unexplained $ 200 million loss in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s investment fund for local governments. The loss has sparked a run on the fund by the local governments, which have withdrawn more than $ 100 million in the past three days. Three annual reports show that investments in the consolidated investment fund's `` pool 100'' totaled $ 773.3 million in 1986. That figure dropped to $ 574.1 million a year later, a decrease of $ 199.2 million. No one can say whether the loss represents reduced interest _ money the state thought it would earn but did n't _ or an actual loss in funds invested. The fund was earning a high rate of interest _ up to 13 percent or more _ during the period when the loss occurred, according to two annual reports for the state <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> and one from the state treasurer's office. State, county and municipal governments put their money into the pool, which the state then invests for them. Treasurer <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> on Tuesday urged a federal investigation into why the fund, which his office manages, suffered the loss. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said he has passed on to the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manchin </ORGANIZATION>'s request that officials determine whether an investigation is warranted. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> has not said whether it will investigate. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> said he does not believe any criminal wrongdoing is involved, just `` bad investments.'' Other probes, including one by the accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Touche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, are under way. Over the past three days, local governments have withdrawn $ 108.9 million _ including $ 41.3 million Wednesday _ in reaction to reports of the loss. Several key people involved in the $ 200 million loss refuse to discuss it. Associate Treasurer <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON>, who was in charge of investments, has said he alerted <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> to the problem and is awaiting the results of the Touche <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> probe. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> oversees all state investments but accused <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON> of not handling the investments properly. He said staff members of the investments office warned <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON> in 1987 that there was a problem, but he said <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON> _ who has resigned to become an administrative aide to Gov.-elect <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> _ ignored them. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> has refused to accept <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON>'s resignation until the loss is cleared up. Former Assistant Treasurer <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lester </PERSON>, who actually made the investments for <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON>, disappeared after quitting the treasurer's office in late 1987 Gov. <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION>, has declined to comment.
