<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-GreatTrek     12-15 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Great Trek,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afrikaners To Celebrate 150th Anniversary of Pioneer Trek</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just before dawn Friday, a few dozen bearded men in leather clothes will take cover behind ox-drawn wagons and fight an imaginary battle against a long-ago defeated Zulu army. The pageant by members of right-wing Afrikaner cultural and political groups will celebrate the Battle of <LOCATION> Blood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and the 150th anniversary of the Great Trek that brought the Dutch-descended pioneers out of the British-ruled <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Colony </LOCATION> into the African wilderness. It wo n't matter that the make-believe battle wo n't be seen by very many people or that it is being staged 20 miles from the government's main celebration at the Pioneer Monument overlooking <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. Most of the events and celebrations are symbolic, and in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> there are many ways of interpreting them. Depending on the interpretation, the 1838 departure of the pioneer families was undertaken to avoid <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s abolition of slavery, to set up a free republic in an unpopulated land, to bring Christianity and civilization to African tribes, or to steal the land of blacks and force them into subjugation. Stories about life on the trek, battles, and religious faith have taken on mythical proportions in the folklore of Afrikaners, the descendants of the pioneers who now dominate the government. The 100th anniversary commemoration in 1938 united Afrikaners, gave impetus to their cultural and political organizations and propelled them to power in the <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> parliamentary victory 10 years later. The right-wingers regard the gradual and limited reforms of apartheid now being made by today's Nationalist government as a betrayal of white rights. They hope this year's celebration will be a catalyst leading to the ouster of the Nationalists and victory for the <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies. A speech by President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to crowds of picnickers at the Pioneer Monument will be broadcast live on national television. The celebrations are the culmination of a four-month re-enactment of the Great Trek by wagons and oxen that converged on <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> this week. Twenty miles away in Donkerhoek, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, its supporters and right-wing groups such as the Nazi-style Afrikaner Reform Movement will be carrying on a more traditional celebration. The right-wingers will dress in 19th-century clothes, listen to poetry and history readings and hold square-dances and sing-a-longs. The Day of the Vow, Dec. 16, is considered a sacred national holiday. It commemorates the 1838 battle at <LOCATION> Blood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Zululand </LOCATION> when one of the pioneer groups vowed to keep the day forever holy if they won the battle against the Zulu King Dingaan the next morning. They did. Most of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s black majority of 26 million, who have no vote in national affairs, do not celebrate the holiday, although they do n't work on the day because the country virtually closes down. A few blacks have participated in the government-sponsored re-enactment as oxen drivers. But the right-wingers have no blacks in their festivities. A coalition of anti-apartheid groups said it would celebrate the day from the view of the losing side in the battle. Blacks, celebrating what they call Heroes Day, will meet in the tribal homeland of KaNgwane to pay homage to the chiefs who fought the whites in the 18th and 19th centuries.
</TEXT>
