<HEAD>New Government Militia Stirs Fears In Philippines</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIANG, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Levetico </PERSON> <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON>, a 51-year-old grandfather, crawled through the brush with his rifle, training to fight communists because he believes they routinely kill old and unproductive people. <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON> is one of 150,000 volunteers the military hopes to recruit into a new militia it describes as essential to defeat communist rebels. Critics fear a new paramilitary will increase human rights abuses against civilians. Military plans call for the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> to consolidate under one banner hundreds of paramilitary and anti-communist vigilante groups to protect villages against the communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. This will help extend government control and curb rights abuses, officials say. In a report today, the London-based group <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said legal safeguards are being ignored and that it has documented evidence of torture and illegal detentions by police, soldiers and paramilitary forces. Human rights groups in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and political commentators also question the wisdom of arming thousands more civilians. `` The trend toward militarization makes people think the only way to contend with our problems is through a military solution,'' said one prominent human rights activist, <PERSON> Mariss </PERSON> <PERSON> Diokno </PERSON>. `` We did not expect that the vigilante groups would be dismantled and be replaced by another group.'' But officers training <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON> and more than 80 other volunteers on the <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, claim the new unit is different. <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON> and the other recruits are lectured on the human rights that are guaranteed by the constitution. Regular and non-commissioned officers will command the new units to ensure they follow regulations, officials said. Like <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON>, most of the volunteers at the makeshift camp in <LOCATION> Liang </LOCATION> were peasant farmers aged 18 to 55. <PERSON> Diwa </PERSON> said in an interview that he joined because he believes that under communism, `` if you are old and unproductive, then they will kill you.'' He said this notion has been reinforced by military officers' lectures on the `` evils of communism.'' At the camp, trainees undergo a five-week crash course including weapons training, basic infantry tactics, self-defense and first aid. After graduating, paramilitary troops move to villages where they live with the people, defend them and gather information on rebels for the army. They get 90 cents a day plus clothing, medical care, housing and firearms. The army `` does not have sufficient manpower to ensure the security of every village,'' Col. <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON>, constabulary commander for <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION>, said in a recent interview. Regular troops will clear areas of rebels and the paramilitary will follow to maintain government control, he said. The government says rebels virtually control 7,800 of the country's 40,832 villages. `` It just depends on who gets there first,'' said a communist political officer who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said the paramilitary would be most effective in areas that have not been infiltrated. Fears about the new unit stem from the <ORGANIZATION> Civilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, a paramilitary force that was established by former President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and that became notorious for rights abuses. President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, who replaced <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> after a military-civilian uprising, promised to disband that force during her 1986 election campaign and now says it will be phased out as the new paramilitary unit is deployed. But military officers admit privately that they often turn to paramilitary veterans to find enough recruits for the new unit. <PERSON> Abelardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Torno </PERSON>, a trainee in <LOCATION> Pampanga </LOCATION> province, said he has belonged to anti-communist militias since the 1960s, including 17 years in the <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. `` All they did was change the name,'' said an officer who stood nearby.
