<HEAD>US Starts Talking To PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said today he would not hesitate to `` break off communications'' with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> if it reneged on its declarations to renounce terrorism and accept <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> defended his decision to permit a dialogue between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials and <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, reversing a 12-year <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government policy, telling reporters that `` words have been spoken'' that spelled out the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s acceptance of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> conditions for direct talks. The president also said that he did n't think <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> had any reason to be upset by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision because `` we have made it very plain that we have not retreated one inch from our position of guaranteeing the safety'' of the Jewish state. The president talked to reporters twice, during picture-taking sessions in the Oval Office with Turkish Prime Minister <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Ozal </PERSON> and later with <LOCATION> Italian </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Ciriaco </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mita </PERSON>. He spoke after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials quickly followed through on the reversal of the longstanding policy against talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, seeking an early meeting. A senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said he hoped that would lead to direct Arab-Israeli peace talks. President-elect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today he supported the president's decision. He added: `` I have n't spelled out any hopes about it. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> met the conditions of the <LOC