<HEAD>LaRouche Case Goes To Jury For Verdict On Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with trial going to jury; picks up 5th graf
pvs, A half-dozen.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s fraud conspiracy trial went to the jury today for a verdict on whether he schemed to cheat tax collectors and lenders who supported his controversial causes. After final closing arguments by defense lawyers and a rebuttal by government prosecutors, Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> sent the case to the jury of eight women and four men who heard testimony during the 15-day trial. <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> said the jurors will deliberate Saturday if necessary to reach a verdict. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>, the 66-year-old political maverick and perennial minor-party presidential candidate, did not testify in his own defense. Defense lawyer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> fund-raisers solicited loans with good faith assurances that they would be repaid, but Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said all the defendants knew the terms of the loans could not be honored. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> told the jurors in the government's rebuttal that supporters who loaned money to the LaRouche movement `` were n't the lifeblood of this organization, these supporters were bled dry.'' `` The organization treated these people with cynicism and disregard'' because everyone knew that the LaRouche organization was `` a bankruptcy waiting to happen,'' he said. The result, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said, was `` an enormous crime _ a $ 30 million crime.'' <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> cautioned the jurors in his instructions that <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s political goals were irrelevant to the case, and <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> insisted that the government was not trying to `` get at <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> or quiet a political movement. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s political movement embraces a number of unorthodox positions and relies heavily on conspiracy theories to explain world events. It has alleged that figures such as <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> and Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> participate in those conspiracies. <PERSON> Larouche </PERSON> backers also have advocated a quarantine for AIDS victims. A half-dozen defense attorneys heaped abuse on the government's case against <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> and six associates as `` garbage'' and a `` rotting carcass'' during closing arguments Tuesday But prosecutors said they had proved that the defendants had conspired to defraud LaRouche supporters by raising more than $ 30 million in loans without any intention of repaying them. In addition, <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> is charged with conspiring to defraud the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> by having all his personal expenses paid by various corporations he controls and pretending he had no taxable income. If convicted on all 13 counts against him, <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> faces a maximum penalty of 65 years in prison and fines totaling $ 3.25 million. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> and his aides deny any wrongdoing. Prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Markham </PERSON> said the government's case had nothing to do with <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s political beliefs but focused on allegedly deceptive fund-raising practices. `` The ends, however noble they may be ... do not justify lying to people to get their money,'' <PERSON> Markham </PERSON> declared. He said <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>'s lenders were `` burned by a group of people who think they are better, and can use the money better, than anyone else.'' But <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> attorney <PERSON> Odin </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> said the government's case was based on `` voodoo conspiracy'' charges that were vague and unfounded. `` They do n't want you to decide straightforward facts,'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> told the jurors. `` They want you to decide garbage.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the `` bad smell'' that sometimes wafted through the courtroom `` came from the rotting carcass of the government's case.'' At one point, the judge admonished defense lawyer <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Gettings </PERSON> for shouting at the jury during an especially impassioned closing argument. Hunched over, his arms flailing and his fingers waggling, <PERSON> Gettings </PERSON> branded as `` liars'' two crucial government witnesses _ both former employees of the LaRouche organization _ who he said were `` openly, vehemently hostile to every defendant in this case.'' <PERSON> Gettings </PERSON> said the defendants had simply borrowed too much money and were unable to repay loans because of government harassment and media attacks that shrank their revenues. <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> and his fund-raisers were n't trying to line their pockets like classic fraud defendants, <PERSON> Gettings </PERSON> said. `` If you do n't find greed, it's impossible to find fraud,'' he said Defense lawyer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said the <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> case was n't about money but `` about a political movement with dedicated followers who want it to succeed and powerful enemies who want it to fail.'' <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> claimed the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> actually wrote the letter that an elderly <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> woman sent to <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON> demanding the return of her loan money. <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> said the letter was an <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> `` entrapment'' attempt against <PERSON> LaRouche </PERSON>.
