<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules Against French-Only Signs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ruled against a <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> law forbidding languages other than French on commercial signs. The court's unanimous 5-0 ruling allows <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> to order French on signs but can not prevent other languages from being used as well. Quebec's premier, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>, is expected to announce his decision Sunday on how the provincial government will comply with the ruling. The language law was passed in 1977 when the separatist Parti Quebecois held power. <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> platform has supported multilingual signs. The court found that the law requiring commercial signs only in French violated the guarantees of freedom of expression provided in the <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> charter. Constitutional lawyers interpreted the ruling as meaning that <PERSON> Bourassa </PERSON> should be able to find some kind of compromise on the issue. `` The judgment makes it consistent with civil liberties,'' lawyer <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Grey </PERSON> said in a live interview with the Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. A majority of <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION> residents speak French as a first language Two separate cases by English-speaking residents challenged the law.
