<HEAD>Police Find First Body In Serial Child Abductions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI TAKETA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police found the naked body of a 4-year-old girl in a campground near <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Thursday, the first confirmed death in a series of crimes against children that have traumatized the city's suburbs A 7-year-old girl and another 4-year-old remain missing in <LOCATION> Saitama </LOCATION> prefecture west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in a series of disappearances that began in August. Six times since October, children at play have been stabbed by strangers in <LOCATION> Saitama </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Chiba </LOCATION> prefecture, east of the capital. None of the stabbing victims, ranging in age from 2 to 4, was fatally injured. Police said they are treating the incidents as cases of sexual perversion. The stabbings and abductions of toddlers by unidentified stalkers have caused panic in the normally placid suburbs. In a country that prides itself on a low crime rate, the crimes also have attracted the nation's attention. `` I never thought a thing like this could happen here,'' a housewife told the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> the night before <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> <PERSON> Namba </PERSON>'s naked body was found in a campground 20 miles from her home. `` We moved here because we thought this would be a good place to raise children.'' Police searched the campground after officials there reported finding articles of clothing with <PERSON> Erika </PERSON>'s name on them. In the middle-class developments where the missing girls lived, hundreds of office workers and high school students have joined police in fruitless searches of playgrounds and nearby scrubland. Housewives have posted fliers bearing likenesses of the girls, all of whom disappeared in the bustling neighborhoods in the afternoon hours after school let out and before darkness fell. Police helicopters and patrol cars have broadcast warnings urging children to get home before dark, and school principals have admonished pupils to avoid strangers and see each other home. But despite a combined turnout of almost 6,000 police officers in <LOCATION> Chiba </LOCATION> and a similar number in <LOCATION> Saitama </LOCATION>, police report no arrests and few leads. On Wednesday, they released a drawing _ based on another child's description _ of a man seen with <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> shortly before she disappeared It showed a face covered by sunglasses and a gauze mask. `` Little children do n't have large vocabularies,'' said <PERSON> Koji </PERSON> <PERSON> Tateishi </PERSON>, an assistant inspector with the <ORGANIZATION> Chiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prefectural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>. In the stabbings, `` what happens to them happens in a flash. They ca n't really tell us about it.'' `` We're treating these as cases of sexual perversion,'' he said. Since <PERSON> Erika </PERSON> was reported missing on Friday and 3-year-old <PERSON> Sachiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> was stabbed in the stomach on a quiet street in <LOCATION> Chiba </LOCATION> a day later, coverage on nightly news programs and in nationwide newspapers has intensified to a level unseen since the kidnap-murder of a small boy in September 1987. The country followed nightly news reports on the ordeal of 5-year-old <PERSON> Yoshiaki </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogiwara </PERSON>. The reports described his abduction near his home, anonymous calls demanding a 20 million yen ransom -LRB- then $ 140,000 -RRB- from his fireman father, and the discovery of the boy's body in a ravine two days later. Outraged media commentators then spoke of the unraveling of Japanese society and waning confidence in a formidable police force that boasted a 1987 record of arrests in 62.6 percent of all reported non-traffic crimes, compared with 20.7 percent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Despite a perceived increase in crimes against children, overall crime in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> actually declined 0.2 percent in 1987. But in the <LOCATION> Chiba </LOCATION> section where <PERSON> Sachiyo </PERSON> <PERSON> Abe </PERSON> was stabbed, fear has curtailed late-afternoon activity at the neighborhood park, housewife <PERSON> Chisato </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiba </PERSON> said. She continues to take her 15-month-old son outside to play, but `` even more than before, I make it a point to watch him very closely,'' she said. `` The thing is, there's really no way to prevent these things.''
