<HEAD>Random Drug Tests Of Secrets Handlers Argued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government does not need evidence of drug abuse to justify random tests of federal officials with access to classified information, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told an appeals court Thursday. Deterrence of drug use among officials in a position to compromise secrets is justification enough to randomly test them, Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is permitted as an employer to make reasonable steps to prevent something from becoming a problem,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said, challenging a lower court's ban on random testing of 4,700 <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials. `` There are enormous national security interests at stake here,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> told a three-judge panel of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The lower court's ruling stopped the drug-testing program from being implemented last summer. `` This is a case about protecting the integrity of those who represent the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in court,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said. `` It's a case about protecting national security, safeguarding grand jury secrecy and preserving the efficacy of criminal prosecution.'' `` The context is a fitness-for-duty test by a public employer,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said of the program that is being challenged by employees who obtained a permanent injunction barring the tests from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON>. Former <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> attorney general <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> urged the panel to uphold <PERSON> Revercomb </PERSON>'s finding that testing without any suspicion of drug use by the individual is an unconstitutional invasion of privacy. <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said the appeals court was `` mandated to weigh and to balance'' the government's interest in testing with the individual employee's constitutional rights to privacy. In doing so, the court must ask: `` Is there a demonstrable existence of a problem?'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has failed to provide `` some kind of data that supports the reasonableness'' of the search, and `` That is the core command of the Fourth Amendment,'' said <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON>, who was once <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. The employees do n't dispute the need to preserve the department's integrity or protect secrets, <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said `` The question is ` how may the department go about enforcing and imposing those accepted requirements?''' `` The department has plenty of ways _ observation of supervisors, background checks, all the less intrusive ways _ to check up on its employees,'' <ORGANIZATION> Sachs </ORGANIZATION> said. But <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> argued that the issue was not evidence of drug use but the types of secrets the employees handled. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employees have access to some of the nation's most closely held secrets, such as information about counter-intelligence and defense programs, such as the stealth bomber `` Stealth technology is something that the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> would crawl over hot coals to get its hands on,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said. But his argument seemed to trouble Chief Judge <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Wald </PERSON>, who questioned when those national security concerns would justify an intrusive search. `` The strongest part of your case is the government's interest,'' <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>. `` It's the other side of the equation, what can trigger this type of testing that bothers me the most.'' There's `` no question we are living in a high-risk society. The question is how far can we go in deterring large risks ... in terms of our constitutional rights,'' <PERSON> Wald </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> argued that <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employees already waived privacy rights when they submitted to extensive <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> background checks and medical examinations. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Silberman </PERSON>, taking up an argument advanced by <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>, suggested that requiring evidence of drug use would mean the government would have to stop testing once it had successfully deterred narcotics abuse among a group of employees. `` The implications of that argument are awful,'' <PERSON> Sachs </PERSON> said. The government `` could suspend the Constitution'' if deterrence were allowed to be the sole justification for drug testing, he said. Both sides urged the court to decide the case without waiting for a ruling by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on two other cases involving drug testing. The high court is reviewing testing of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents seeking promotion and railway crews involved in accidents. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Spottswood </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> also sat on the panel, which gave no indication when it would rule.
