<HEAD>Arafat's Gamble Could Cause Radical Backlash</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American decision to talk with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> is the biggest step toward <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace in a decade, but radical Palestinians called <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> a traitor Thursday and said the bloodshed will continue. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>'s renunciation of terrorism and recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist, coupled with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response after years of shunning the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, is the most dramatic development since <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> signed a peace treaty with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1979 His move could be the turning point in the 40 years of <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict, but it also is the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman's greatest gamble and could explode in his face. Such radical Palestinian factions as the <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> group may launch a new wave of terrorism intended to wreck the initiative. Militants within the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> have stayed their hands for the moment, but many feel <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> made too many concessions. The <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, a Marxist group that reconciled with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> last year after a four-year estrangement, accused him of `` capitulation.'' Its leader, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>, said in a statement sent to The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, that it welcomed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision but felt <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> acted only to `` end the diplomatic isolation that followed its refusal to grant Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> a visa to go to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' `` Therefore, we urge our masses to keep up the struggle to force <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to recognize the state of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> and all legitimate Palestinin rights,'' he said. After the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refused <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> a visa to address the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the assembly moved its session to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON>, who leads a Syrian-based breakaway faction called Fatah-Uprising, said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was `` a traitor ... for his surrenderist concessions to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> enemy.'' A Mousa spokesman accused the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman later of paying `` an exhorbitant price, the recognition of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, for this American decision'' and declared: `` <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is not able to fulfill his commitments, especially his commitment to give up the armed struggle against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Mousa </PERSON> and other dissidents left the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 in a Syrian-supported mutiny. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON> <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON> of the Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, also backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, said in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>: `` <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has recognized -LRB- <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> -RRB- and offered four-fifths of the Palestinian land to'' the Jewish state. `` By renouncing violence and terrorism, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is condemning anyone who uses the gun against the Israeli occupier,'' <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has offered <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> what he does n't have. The land of <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION> is not the property of any organization or any individual.'' Six weeks ago, West German authorities arrested 13 people suspected of belonging to <PERSON> Jibril </PERSON>'s group who said they were planning terrorist attacks. The extremist <PERSON> Saiqa </PERSON> faction, whose name in Arabic means `` lightning,'' said in <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION>: `` We shall see to it that the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> gets back on its original revolutionary course of struggle.'' <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> and his lieutenants would be targets of the radicals, along with Israelis and Americans. Since his first hints at moderation 15 years ago, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> has had to fight not only the Israelis but Palestinian extremists and hard-line <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations led by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, has sought for years to gain control of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. Gunmen working for <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> have killed a score of <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> aides, and the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> secret service has assassinated others. The last victim of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Wazir </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> chairman's right-hand man, shot to death April 16 at his home in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, according to <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> security sources. Last month, <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> steered the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> legislature to implicitly recognizing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by accepting <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Resolutions 242 and 338 as the basis of an international <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> also declared an independent state, presumably to be located in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, where Palestinians have been in revolt against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation for a year. <PERSON> Habash </PERSON>'s guerrilla group and others went along with the compromise at the <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION> meeting for the sake of unity, but <PERSON> Habash </PERSON> said to <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>: `` We're backing your efforts because this is what the majority wants, but we do n't believe moderation will pay. We ca n't wait forever. If you fail, you have to come back to this council to say so and we can then decide the future course.''
