<HEAD>City Council Bans Beepers In Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The City Council has unanimously approved an ordinance banning beepers in all public and private schools, a move educators hope will put a dent in drug sales and prostitution. `` We know their mothers are not beeping them,'' <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said earlier at a committee meeting. School officials say students are often beeped in classrooms to make drug deals or to engage in prostitution. `` We've got girls 11 years old. They get a call and they're out of school to turn a trick,'' public schools security chief <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said. The beeper ban was part of an omnibus ordinance approved by aldermen Wednesday. School Superintendent <PERSON> Manford </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> issued an executive order in September banning the beepers, but <PERSON> Sims </PERSON> said the result was irate parents who did n't like being called down to school because of the infraction. The ordinance takes the issue out of the hands of school administrators and gives it to the police. Violators are subject to fines of $ 200 to $ 500.
