<HEAD>Waiting Period on New Sales Starts Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A city ordinance requiring handgun purchasers to wait 15 days before picking up their weapons goes into effect Friday. The law requires the wait between sale and receipt of a handgun to allow police time to check whether the prospective buyer has a criminal record or is mentally incompetent. Until now, guns could be picked up immediately and police had to track the buyers down if there were reasons to prevent them from buying guns. <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>'s ordinance is based on an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> law that allows cities to enact local gun control measures. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which lobbied against the ordinance, said <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>'s law goes farther than measures in other cities because it applies to individuals who sell guns, as well as to commercial gun dealers. The law requires anyone selling, renting, leasing or transferring ownership or possession of a handgun to notify police of the transaction and fill out an application form. Forms are available at police district stations and the city <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> offices. The ordinance does not cover rifles or shotguns. Violation is a first-degree misdemeanor with a maximum $ 1,000 fine and six months in jail. Three stores in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> now sell handguns. Retailers say it is too soon to tell what impact the ordinance will have on sales.
</TEXT>
