<HEAD>Future Teachers Get Free College Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fifteen of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s best and brightest high school seniors are being enticed into the teaching profession in a corporate-sponsored scholarship program. The 15 students introduced Wednesday as Academy of Educators Scholars will receive a free, four-year education if they graduate from college and teach for at least five years. And if they land a classroom job in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the students will receive a $ 12,000 bonus. `` All my friends are aspiring lawyers and aspiring physicians, and all of them want to make a lot of money,'' said <PERSON> Afrika </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, 17. `` I never wanted to be a nurse or a firewoman, I always wanted to be a teacher.'' The program offered by the Foundation for Excellence in Teaching is being financed by <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GATX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and a number of individuals. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Koldyke </PERSON>, who helped start the foundation, said the program is an investment in the city's youth. `` In the venture capital business, you have to project for the future ... and this is the future,'' said <PERSON> Koldyke </PERSON>, general partner of <ORGANIZATION> Frontenac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a venture capital firm. The program and others like it have the support of the 680,000-member <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teachers </ORGANIZATION>, which has lobbied <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for a similar federal program, said spokesman <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Treibitz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washingto