<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Following a 76-year-old holiday tradition, about 2,000 Alaskans lined up in the slush to get a rare look inside the governor's mansion, shake the chief executive's hand and sip warm cider. Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, played host at the Christmas open house Wednesday night for the third consecutive year in the colonial mansion overlooking the state capital. Except for two years during World War II, the open house has been an annual event since the imposing, three-story home was built for territorial Gov. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> in 1912. `` I've been to about 38 of them out of the 40 years I've been here,'' said 92-year-old <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>. `` This is my house and I love it.'' The feeling that the house is a state treasure that belongs to all Alaskans brings them out in every shape, age and occupation. `` You would n't be able to get away with it in a place with more population,'' said <PERSON> Koren </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosworth </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Juneau </LOCATION>'s 30,000 residents. `` It's nice. It gives people a feeling they're part of it.'' Guests mingled about the main floor of the 15-room mansion carrying plates of food and cups of cider or punch, while the Cowpers and Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> McAlpine </PERSON> and his wife greeted people. The upstairs living quarters and the basement were off limits. In the living room, guests were entertained by violinists and a chorus, while children lined up to talk to <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> and Mrs. <PERSON> Claus </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiscus </PERSON>, who was sampling the refreshments with her 12-year-old daughter <PERSON> Robin </PERSON>, said they attend the open house every year. The governor's chef, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> DeCherney </PERSON>, and the mansion staff begin planning for the three-hour affair in July. Baking begins in September and most of the cookies, breads and hors d'oeuvres are stored in the freezer. This year the treats included 1,500 egg rolls, 1,400 artichoke pastries, 1,350 sausage pastries, 1,400 deviled eggs and 20 pounds of Brie cheese stuffed with apples and pears. By the end, only a few treats remained. For many, the open house has become a family tradition. Some parents brought video cameras, while others took snapshots. The largest attendance at the open house came in 1983, when an estimated 4,000 people filed through the mansion. Interest was sparked that year by controversy over a $ 2.7 million mansion restoration and redecoration project during the term of former Gov. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheffield </PERSON>. The state foots the bill for the open house, with expenses coming out of the mansion budget, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramseur </PERSON> said.
