 A mail handler shot three co-workers in the main <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> post office, then holed up inside for 13 hours with his girlfriend as a hostage, firing birdshot at random from under a door today, authorities said. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> threw out his shotgun and surrendered this morning after all-night telephone negotiations with <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and police, including a cousin who is a police officer. His girlfriend appeared unhurt, said <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>. The rampage was prompted by <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s concern for the welfare of his two children in his wife's custody in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Police Superintendent <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON>, who got him to surrender. `` I just tried to appeal to him as a father,'' <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said. None of the three co-workers hit by birdshot from <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>'s gun suffered life-threatening wounds, hospital officials said. One person was shot in the eye. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, who is about 40, was a six-year mail handler who had recently been promoted but whose wife had left him, post office spokesman <PERSON> Cesta </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON> said. `` He feels like he does n't like the conditions which they -LRB- his children -RRB- are living under, and I assured him that I would look into that,'' <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said. `` And if his kids are being neglected, I would do all I could to try to get some intervention to maybe get the kids back here in the custody of their grandmother.'' <PERSON> Woodfork </PERSON> said <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> was n't angry at his girlfriend and co-worker, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, 29. `` After the shooting started he just grabbed her,'' the police superintendent said. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> made only o