<HEAD>Foreign Teams Head Home as Hope for Finding Survivors Fades</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto VIE1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPITAK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign relief workers said Thursday they were giving up hope of finding more survivors of the Armenian earthquake, and crews prepared to evacuate the last residents of this hard-hit town and raze it. <PERSON> Nouradian </PERSON> <PERSON> Norig </PERSON> <PERSON> Kritkorianizh </PERSON>, the first secretary of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview that crews would take measures to prevent infectious diseases and begin razing the city on Sunday About 15,000 of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>'s 25,000 people died in the Dec. 7 quake that destroyed most of city, he said. Altogether, the quake killed 55,000 people in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and left 500,000 of the area's 700,000 people homeless. Foreign relief experts and Soviet officials said hope was fading to find more survivors, and the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said searchers had found only one person alive in the past 24 hours. That person was found in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, it said. Voices and other signs of life in the ruins of destroyed cities dropped off sharply after Monday night, when temperatures plummeted to below freezing, <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Foreign Disaster Assistance office said at a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> news conference. `` The hope of finding any more -LRB- survivors -RRB- is ended,'' she said. Green military vans with mounted speakers toured the muddy streets asking people to leave. Most women and children already were gone. `` We believe the evacuation will take about three days,'' <PERSON> Kritkorianizh </PERSON> said. About 5,000 men needed to begin rebuilding the city in early spring will be given temporary housing about one mile from <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, he said. Trucks were distributing milk, bread, sausages, meat and oranges to the survivors in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, where it remained cold and damp. Some people had set up what was left of their household belongings _ upholstered chairs, mattresses and even an occassional brass bed _ around crackling bonfires where it was warmer than inside tents. A large group of people were pressing against the gates of what was once the city's central market, where soldiers were distributing warm coats. Soviet officials vowed to continue the search until there is no more hope of bringing people out alive but said no more doctors or fire brigades are needed. `` Yesterday -LRB- Wednesday -RRB- Health Minister <PERSON> Yevgenvy </PERSON> <PERSON> Chazov </PERSON> said the search was to continue but that with the lapse of time hopes grow smaller and smaller. They are still looking for people in the ruins,'' <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said at a news briefing. Teams from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> have already returned home. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON>, head of the 14-member <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said he doubted anybody was still alive. `` If I thought there was someone still alive I would not be sitting here,'' <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> told reporters at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport. <PERSON> McMartin </PERSON> said his group was physically exhausted and that the Soviets were beginning to employ bulldozers, making it difficult for them to use their high technology equipment to find victims. Rows of bulldozers were seen parked a few blocks from the main square in <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s second-largest city located to the west of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Reid </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION>, said the Soviets had decided to call off the search and rescue on Dec. 20 and that some of the foreign relief teams were leaving. `` It is a terrible dilemna for authorities caught between the need for proper sanitation and the need to respect relatives who are still hanging on,'' he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. He said that 25,000 bodies had been counted based on figures provided to the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> by the Soviet Council of Ministers. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that 21,755 bodies had been identified and counted so far. Thousands of corpses remained buried in rubble. `` There is a danger of typhoid, cholera, and dysentery from the poor sanitation in the disaster area which has likely led to contamination of the water supply by insects and rodents,'' Dr. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Borg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Netherlands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> said in an interview in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. Reporters visitng <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> on Thursday saw hundreds of sacks of lime piled at a hospital, apparently in preparation for spreading on corpses. While the relief teams were pulling out, looters were moving in. Police have detained 179 people accused of stealing foreign relief packages and looting in the last 24 hours, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Monstrous as it sounds, there are also others _ better described as shadows rather than as human beings.. They roam around the ruins _ not looking anybody in the face, they roam around the ruins _ not to save but to steal,'' <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s Deputy Interior Minister <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>.
