<HEAD>Censors Approve Controversial Director's Film</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Film censors in their first open meeting ever approved a controversial movie about a young man who can not cope with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s new competition and commits suicide, an official paper said Thursday. The censors decided that the movie, tentatively titled `` Transmigration,'' can be released uncut to Chinese theaters, the Guangming Daily said. The movie is directed by <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> <PERSON> Jianxin </PERSON> and produced by the <ORGANIZATION> Xian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studio </ORGANIZATION>, which in recent years has produced <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most technically innovative and politically daring films. <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>'s first feature movie, `` The Black Cannon Incident'' in 1985, was cut by censors but still caused an uproar with its attack on mindless bureaucracy. It told the story of a telegraphed message about a missing chess piece that was misinterpreted by officials as a message about a real cannon. The Guangming Daily said censors in the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> discussed <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>'s new movie in a two-hour session that was open to journalists for the first time. It did not say if the censors plan to make all their meetings open. Few Chinese films have dealt with the impact on ordinary lives of the economic reforms of the past decade, in which central planning and social welfare guarantees have been reduced in favor of the free market. Although the incomes of most Chinese have risen dramatically, some have actually slid and many people are unable or unwilling to obtain jobs or promotions based on merit. By showing the underside of the new competition in which some ca n't keep up, <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>'s movie could be seen as an indirect attack on government policy. But he said in an interview earlier this year that this was not his intent. The 34-year-old director said his goal was not to provoke controversy but to `` make films that reflect social problems'' so they can be corrected. The Guangming Daily said the censors decided that the movie `` is an authentic and honest attempt to portray the reactions of young people to the reform era in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and has artistic appeal.'' For decades, censors met privately and without objective guidelines to rule on the acceptability of movies and other entertainment. The Ministry of Culture is drafting a law that would establish rules for what is permissible. Although this would reduce the power of individual censors, some artists have expressed fears the law will halt the current process of gradual experimentation and liberalization.
</TEXT>
