<FIRST>r w AM-CountryHam     12-15 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Country Ham,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Still Not Ready To Issue New Rules on Country Ham Processing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once again the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is going to let processors keep on making old-fashioned country hams until paperwork on a new food safety requirment is completed. The deadline for ham producers to comply with new federal regulations was supposed to be Dec. 31, 1988. But then the previous deadline was supposed to be last Dec. 31. And the one before that was Dec. 31, 1986. There also was one on Aug. 6, 1985. Now, the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday, the new deadline will be Dec. 31, 1989 _ or whenever the agency finally approves the new rules, spokeswoman <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Goins </PERSON> said. The lengthy rule-making procedure involves those hams often seen on grocery shelves in cloth bags, or hanging from rafters in country stores. They must be scrubbed to remove mold and then soaked or boiled a couple of times to reduce the salt content. They're the kind of hams for which someone had to invent red-eye gravy and, in some parts of the country, grits. As the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> defines them, they're `` uncooked, cured, dried, smoked or unsmoked pork products made from solid meat.'' Typically, country or dry-cured hams are treated with salt and then put in a smokehouse to cure and age, a total process that can take months or even years. Most hams sold in supermarkets are wet-cured quickly in brine solutions and cooked before sale to consumers. In March 1983 the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> proposed rules intended to help prevent trichinosis, a disease caused by microscopic parasitic worms, or trichinae, that can occur in improperly cooked pork. The proposed rules were directed at ready-to-eat pork products and dry-cured country hams. Shortly after the original proposal was adopted on Feb. 6, 1985, the agency learned that some federally inspected ham producers were using old-fashioned methods that did n't meet the new <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> requirements and were ordered to show by Aug. 6, 1985, that their curing procedures were safe. The country ham industry protested, so the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> allowed more time. One compelling reason for the extensions of time for compliance was that no trichina problems had been associated with the dry-cured hams. `` These traditional processing methods have been permitted because they are decades-old methods believed to be effective in destroying trichinae,'' says <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prucha </PERSON>, acting administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> agency. `` We are researching the safety of traditional trichina control methods and developing a proposed rule for issuance in early 1989,'' he said. `` After we receive public comments on that proposal, we will develop new regulations.'' But just in case the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s rule-making machine is slower than officials hope, the compliance deadline was extended another full year.
</TEXT>
