<HEAD>Bush Avoids One Problem, But Inherits Another</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agreement to talk with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> spares President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> one politically difficult decision, but gives him another arduous task: overseeing that dialogue. The decision by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> adminstration guarantees that the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>'s explosive problems will face <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as soon as he enters the Oval Office on Jan. 20, even though the vice president said Thursday, `` There's no game plan, there's no five-point program.'' Although initial contacts with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> are to begin in <LOCATION> Tunis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tunisia </LOCATION>, later this week, there is little doubt that the turnabout decision clears the way for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to try to bring <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> into direct negotiations. With tensions high on both sides of the 40-year-old dispute, such a task could be monumental. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> not only will have to deal with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, whom just a week before the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> adminstration had branded a terrorist, but he'll have to do it in a way that avoids souring relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stressed Thursday that the initiative, which he fully supported, was `` a dialogue, not negotations.'' `` Let's see how things evolve. My position remains the same. I want to see direct talks between, for example, between King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and the Israelis,'' he told reporters. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </P