<HEAD>Educators Ask Congressional Panel To Boost Federal Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix duplicate numbering.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government needs to funnel more money to the nation's colleges and universities and to the students who wish to attend them, a group of educators told a congressional panel on Thursday. Witnesses appearing before the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s education and health subcommittee said that diverting more resources to post-secondary education would pay off in the long run with a higher-skilled work force `` What we have done up to the present time in order to create a work force as motivated, skilled and dedicated as those we confront in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and other industrialized nations has obviously not been adequate and can even be called tragically inadequate,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Trachtenberg </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The subcommittee released a report on Wednesday, the first day of the two-day hearing, that recommended ways to better American schools, including lengthening the school year, improving vocational education and other programs, and increasing the emphasis on basic skills such as reading and studying. But on Thursday, the panel's chairman, Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, emphasized what he said was a need to consider making post-secondary education available to all qualified students. `` Kindergarten through grade 12 education, which was adequate for the work force of a predominantly agricultural nation adapting to industrialization, is simply obsolete in today's complex and sophisticated high-tech environment,'' <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON> said. The educators who addressed the committee agreed, and argued that federal aid to colleges and universities has eroded in rec