<HEAD>Panel Concerned About Earthquake Safety at Savannah River Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A scientific advisory panel has urged the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> to bolster the resistance to earthquakes of a weapons production reactor at the trouble-plagued <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION>. The panel also has concluded that to avoid confusion during a crisis, fewer personnel should be regularly assigned to the control room of the K reactor at the facility near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, S.C. The reactor currently is shut down because of maintenance and safety concerns. The recommendations came in a letter, released Thursday, to Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> from the department's <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Nuclear Facility Safety, which <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> established earlier this year to assess safety programs at the nuclear plant. The three reactors at <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> are the nation's only source for tritium, a radioactive isotope of hydrogen vital to boosting the explosive power of modern nuclear warheads. Because tritium decays at a rate of 5.5 percent a year, it needs to be replenished regularly. The advisory committee, chaired by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, declined to endorse a detailed DOE report presenting the department's strategy for restarting the K reactor. The just-completed DOE report outlined more than 160 separate tasks, calling for a complete overhaul of training, safety, management, operating and inspection procedures. In the advisory panel's 11-page letter to <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> said that `` in our opinion ... the restart strategy document represents only an initial step in <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to develop sound operations at <ORGANIZATION> SRP </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plant </LOCATION> -RRB-.'' He added that `` we have broad concerns regarding safety philosophy, the overall criteria for restart and management.'' A DOE spokesman, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmets </PERSON>, said in response to the letter: `` Secretary <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> has received this very constructive document. We believe that this an important part of the process, and we will respond in due course. Secretary <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> takes very seriously the recommendations of the advisory committee.'' Regarding earthquakes, <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> wrote, `` the seismic resistance issue in the restart strategy appears to be narrowly focused, does not indicate what must be completed before restart and tends to weaken the defense-in-depth philosophy.'' `` The seismic resistance criterion requires the capability to shut down, cool and monitor core status for a design basis earthquake -LRB- 0.2 g -RRB-, but it is not stated whether or not this needs to be completed before startup,'' he said. The `` g'' figure represents the strength of shaking that a structure undergoes during an earthquake. A level of 0.2 g would be approximately equivalent to the force exerted by a nearby quake with a magnitude of 6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> noted in the letter that `` seismic criteria for the confinement system and the ECS -LRB- emergency core cooling system -RRB- were not included because neither is considered to be a ` primary safety system.' Crucial instruments are to be seismically qualified, but the instrumentation system -LRB- wiring, sensors, etc. -RRB- is neglected.'' `` We recommend that the ECS and confinement systems be seismically upgraded prior to restart,'' he said. Overall, <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> wrote, `` a rationale should be developed for deciding which upgrades are of immediate concern, which can be delayed until after restart and for how long.'' On the control room issue, the letter to <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> said current plans call for at least 12 people being in the K reactor control room when the reactor is restarted. They include five reactor operators, a technical support engineer, a shift adviser, a DOE <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> office onsite engineer, an environmental safety and health inspector, a DOE headquarters observer, a contractor oversight representative and a contract operations manager. `` This number is clearly excessive,'' <PERSON> Ahearne </PERSON> wrote. `` Indeed, it is difficult to see how such a large group could communicate effectively to provide prompt attention to any crisis situation. The list of people required for plant control room duties should be reviewed carefully and access limited to essential personnel.''
