<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge in the Iran-Contra case on Thursday scheduled a hearing for Dec. 21 to begin making final preparations for the trial of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>, who has previously indicated the trial could begin as early as late January, said in an order that he wanted to discuss procedures for screening potential jurors and other pre-trial housekeeping matters. The scheduling order provided yet another indication that <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> is determined to take the case to a speedy trial. On Monday, he strictly limited the number of classified documents that North can introduce into evidence and set a Jan. 3 deadline for listing those secrets he would propose to disclose at the trial. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>'s rulings on secret documents earlier this week greatly increased the likelihood that all the charges against the former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> aide will go to trial despite <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration refusal to release secret documents the defense wants to publicly disclose. Under the Classified Information Procedures Act, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> could still dismiss the central conspiracy charge against <PERSON> North </PERSON> if he determines that the withheld documents are needed to ensure that <PERSON> North </PERSON> gets a fair trial. But the judge made clear that he would not allow <PERSON> North </PERSON> to introduce documents that were not relevant to his defense simply to scuttle his prosecution. North is accused of conspiring to illegally divert U.S.-Iran arms-sale profits to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. He faces a total of 14 felony counts, including charges he lied to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, destroyed documents, pocketed travelers checks intended for the Contra leaders and illegally used a tax-exempt foundation to raise money to arm the rebels. Three co-defendants are set to be tried separately after <PERSON> North </PERSON>. At next week's hearing, the judge said he wanted to consider the type of questionnaire that would be sent to prospective jurors. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said he also wanted to set a deadline for independent counsel <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walsh </PERSON> to provide <PERSON> North </PERSON>'s lawyers with the grand jury testimony of the prosecution witnesses. The defense is entitled to examine that testimony to prepare cross examination. Questionnaires are usually sent to jurors for lengthy or high-profile criminal cases, such as the perjury trial of former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deaver </PERSON>. The questions are designed to screen out jurors who would be unable to serve for a variety of reasons, including their inability to render a fair verdict or to understand complicated evidence. The completed questionnaires would be used as a basis to conduct jury selection in court. The North trial, which could last several months, may require the court to order as many as 1,000 questionnaires to screen out people who are unable to serve for the duration of the proceeding. The questionnaire would likely also ask prospective jurors whether they could judge the evidence in the case free of any influence from the extensive publicity that has surrounded the Iran-Contra affair.
