<FIRST>r i AM-SpermDonor     12-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sperm Donor,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Denies Visitation Rights To Sperm Donor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Dutch court on Thursday denied visitation rights to a sperm donor who sued for permission to visit his biological child, a court spokesman said. In the case, which has gained widespread national attention, a man who donated his sperm to a woman in a lesbian relationship sought the right to periodically meet the 15-month-old daughter born as a result of the artificial insemination. The donor claimed that an `` emotional attachment'' to the child developed over visits to the lesbian couple before and after the birth. A month ago, the Utrecht court ruled that the father was entitled `` in principle'' to sue for his rights. But Dutch family law does not contain specific provisions outlining the rights of sperm donors. The identities of both the plaintiff and the defendants in the lawsuit were not disclosed for reasons of privacy, and court hearings six weeks ago took place behind closed doors. In its ruling Thursday, the court said that `` in this particular case, the tensions caused by periodical visits would be very serious, and that is not in the interest of the child.'' The ruling also said that `` in cases such as this, visitation rights should only be granted in extraordinary circumstances.'' It did not elaborate. During the hearings, the lesbian couple claimed that the friendship with the donor had ended and that serious personal conflicts had developed, according to their lawyer, <PERSON> Arnoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Willems </PERSON>. He added that the couple had rejected the idea of an anonymous donor so that the father could be identified if the child later would ask for his name. Artificial insemination by donated sperm is a widespread practice in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, but the strict confidentiality that prevents identification of the parties involved usually precludes such legal battles.
</TEXT>
