<HEAD>Tobacco Quotas Raised</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For the second consecutive year, flue-cured tobacco farmers in 1989 will see a hefty boost in federal marketing quotas, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. Deputy Secretary <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said the 1989 flue-cured quota will be 890.5 million pounds, up 18 percent from this year's 755 million pounds. The national acreage allotment will be increased to 426,485 acres from 379,588 acres in 1988. Allowing for overmarketings and undermarketings, the effective quota for 1989 will be up by about 90 million pounds from this year. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said the flue-cured price support will be boosted to $ 1.468 per pound, an increase of 2.6 cents from 1988. The basic quota was increased on the 1988 flue-cured tobacco crop for the first time since 1975, according to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> analysts, reflecting a draw-down on stockpiles and brisk demand. <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said flue-cured tobacco farmers will vote in a mail referendum to be held Jan. 9-12 on whether to continue federal marketing quotas for the following three years, 1990, 1991 and 1992. A two-thirds majority will be required for the controls to continue.
