<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading advocate for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children on Thursday urged President-elect <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to make good on his campaign promises to offer more government help to disadvantaged youth, saying that eventually would save tax money as well as lives. <PERSON> Marian </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, president of the private Children's Defense Fund, said the 1988 elections brought children's needs into the national spotlight, and that `` the debate over the next four to eight years will be on the form, level and timetable'' of programs to help youngsters and improve child care In a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign proposal for a $ 2.2 billion children's tax credit is a `` welcome supplement'' to the child care bill that was considered but not enacted by the outgoing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> She noted <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also called during the campaign for support of the federal nutrition program for pregnant women and children, increased <ORGANIZATION> Head </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Start </ORGANIZATION> education efforts, expanded Medicaid health coverage for low-income families, and new education initiatives. `` I have confidence that he will keep his word,'' Ms. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said. `` ... I look forward, on many occasions, beginning in the State of the Union address, to his fulfilling it.'' She said that failing to meet children's needs early in life results in more costly problems later. `` At a time of massive deficits, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> can not afford to waste resources by failing to prevent and curb the deficits which cripple our children and cost billions in later remedial and custodial dollars,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>'s remarks were excerpted from her organization's upcoming report, `` A Children's Defense Budget: A Vision for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Children,'' to be released in January 1989 She recited a litany of troubling statistics about the levels of children living in poverty, infant mortality, gaps in prenatal care, low birthweight babies, children infected with the AIDS virus, broken families and homelessness. But she added: `` This is, for all its shadows, not a gloom and doom speech. It is a get-off-our-national-duff and save-our-future speech.'' Ms. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said her organization's most immediate goals include: health insurance for poor families, expanding the federal nutrition program to cover all pregnant women, infants and children, making Head Start available to all needy children, ensuring that all children are fully immunized, making quality child care available to all families, and increasing the minimum wage. `` We believe these goals are doable in four or five years and should be pursued as fast as the delivery systems of these successful programs can effectively serve more children,'' she said. `` The longer we wait the more children we will lose.''
