<HEAD>Foundation Scandal: AG Says It Was Charity for the Rich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Directors of a charitable foundation were accused Thursday of siphoning off nearly $ 7 million to support their own lavish habits, including chauffeured limousines, nights at the opera and trips to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. In a lawsuit filed in state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, state Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said officials of the <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Frances </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spingold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> systematically looted the organization's coffers from 1983 to 1988, depleting its assets by almost 50 percent In particular, <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON>, the foundation's chief administrative officer, took more than $ 5 million in salary to perform `` simple administrative duties. <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> said <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> _ and not the charities he was supposed to support _ was the chief beneficiary of the foundation. <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> lawyer, allegedly billed the foundation at a rate of $ 275 to $ 350 an hour for his services. His hours increased, according to the attorney general's office, from an average of 29 per week in 1984 to an average of 77 per week in 1986 and 1987. In its lawsuit, the attorney general's office demanded the removal of <PERSON> Halperin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Melvyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitan </PERSON> as directors of the foundation and demanded repayment of losses resulting from their alleged misconduct. At <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>' request, state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Justice <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauchamp </PERSON> <PERSON> Ciparick </PERSON> issued a temporary restrainin