<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A dozen children and teen-agers seemed to be enjoying themselves Thursday rummaging through boxes of clothes and toys. But the laughter and the smiles vanished as they remembered they did n't have a home or parents to return to. Eight days after an earthquake in northwestern <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> sundered homes and families, officials can only guess at the number of children killed or left orphans. Many survivors are having nightmares, and the Soviet Children's Fund, a charity, sent a team of 11 child psychologists to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> to help `` Who has trouble sleeping?'' psychologist <PERSON> Valeria </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukhina </PERSON> asked the group of children, whose parents are dead or missing. Nearly all raised their hands and yelled, `` I do, I do!'' The therapy session had begun. The youngsters, from seven to 15 years old, were sitting in a recital hall of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>'s music conservatory. The building was converted into a children's relief center and the hall was filled with donated toys and clothes. `` Sit back and close your eyes,'' the pscychologist told the children. `` Frightening pictures may come to you. But forget about everything. Force yourself to see the best: the sky, birds.'' The children broke in with their own suggestions: flowers, a warm sun. Their eyes still closed, children were told to imagine themselves in a forest and told to care for dolls they had just received. <PERSON> Mukhina </PERSON> seemed to be trying to establish the dolls as a symbol of security to replace that which was lost with the disappearance of their parents. `` Hold the doll, which loves you,'' she said, pushing the new toys into the children's embrace. `` Take care of the dolls. Lead them into the world. Keep everything frightening away from your doll.' Then she concluded: `` When I count to three you will say goodbye to your forest and tonight you will rejoin it and sleep peacefully. The suggestion worked so well that 12-year-old <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> <PERSON> Chudliny </PERSON> did n't open her eyes again when the count ended. But when she woke up, the shock of the quake returned and she began to cry. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Likhanov </PERSON>, head of the Children's Fund, was watching and went over to embrace <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> and comfort her. <PERSON> Lena </PERSON>'s 15-year-old brother <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON> told in a matter-of-fact way what he could not get out of his mind. `` We had an English class. We sat writing. The teacher said tomorrow there will be a quiz. Then everything started to shake,'' <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON> said, recalling when the quake struck his hometown of <LOCATION> Leninakan </LOCATION> at 11:41 a.m. `` ` Let's get out!' we shouted,'' <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON> said. A classmate of <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON>'s, who identified himself as <PERSON> Saak </PERSON>, described how the class managed to get outside and saw one entire class crushed as they tumbled from the third floor to the ground. Soldiers later pulled up in a tank and took the students away. <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON> said he does n't know what happened to his parents. In an interview, <PERSON> Mukhina </PERSON> explained that she tries to help the children cope with the tragedy by `` replacing negative emotions with good thoughts.'' But she said the process is likely to take years. In the meantime the children are staying in a <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> school, playing with their new toys and going to movies and concerts. Authorities are arranging longer term care in sanitariums throughout the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexanyants </PERSON>, an Armenian doctor specializing in child health care. Some Armenians say the children should be kept in the small southern republic of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> rather than being sent out to other parts of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Alexanyants </PERSON> said all eventually will return.
