<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday gave <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials two months to adopt an automobile pollution inspection plan for the <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> area or face a cutoff of $ 20 million in federal highway funds. Unless the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> complies with the federal Clean Air Act by ordering tailpipe inspections in populous <LOCATION> Cuyahoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, which includes <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, federal highway money to the county will be blocked 60 days after the order is published in the Federal Register. In addition, carbon monoxide-spewing smokestack industries will be denied new construction permits, and air pollution control grants to <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> will be reduced by $ 64,000 under the sanctions given final <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> approval. If those penalties do n't prod state lawmakers into enacting a tailpipe inspection bill, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> is ready to wield yet another club: the loss of sewage construction grant money, perhaps $ 20 million worth. Spokeswomen for Gov. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Celeste </PERSON> and the state <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said avoiding the sanctions has become a top priority for the new year. `` We are working with the governor's office on draft legislation which we hope to introduce as early as possible in January,'' <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Maier </PERSON> said. `` I would give the federal government what they've asked for.'' Press Secretary <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said the governor believes there is time to beat the 60-day deadlin