<HEAD>Defense Minister Accuses US of Continuing to Supply Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Defense Minister <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> accused the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration Thursday of continuing supply flights to Nicaraguan rebels in violation of a congressional ban. Gen. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, whose brother <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> is president of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, also told a news conference that battle casualties in 1988 were dramatically lower than the previous year's total. He claimed Nicaraguan radar detected 10 clandestine supply flights into <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in November. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has supported the rebels, known as Contras, since 1981, two years after a civil war in which the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> deposed the late President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> stopped <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the rebels at the end of February but allowed distribution of non-lethal aid to continue in neighboring <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. About 10,000 rebels returned to base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> to get the food and uniforms. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said rebel forces totaled no more than 7,000, of whom about 2,000 were in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. He said the presence of Contras in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> means a war situation still exists and the rebels `` can do damage.'' <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has an army of about 80,000, the largest in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and gets its military equipment from the Soviet bloc. The defense minister said government forces killed 2,226 rebels in 1988, down from 5,339 the previous year, and 611 Sandinista soldiers were killed compared with 1,613 in 1987. He said civilian casualties rose to 1,748 from 1,675 in 1987, but did not break the number down into dead and wounded. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said the number rose because of kidnappings by rebel forces. The Sandinistas and Contras signed a cease-fire March 23 that called for the rebels to stop fighting in exchange for democratic concessions. Talks on details of the agreement reached a stalemate in September. Both sides stopped offensive operations March 21, when the talks began. The government has renewed the cease-fire each month since a formal 60-day truce ended May 31. On Thursday, the defense minister claimed the Contras had killed 69 civilians since the March agreement, wounded 79 and kidnapped 372. He said 70 soldiers had been killed, 73 were wounded and seven were missing. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, flanked by the military high command, said Nicaraguans should be prepared for a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> invasion. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have made that claim repeatedly. He said Honduran forces have harassed Nicaraguan positions on the border to provoke a confrontation that would give <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> an excuse to request help from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
