<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal election officials, under court order to clarify how political parties can spend campaign funds, heard Democratic and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> spokesman warn Thursday that too much regulation could stamp out politicking at the local level. While other critics told the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that current rules have led to illegal use of so-called soft money, the national political parties lobbied for flexibility in what the state and local parties can do. The issue revolves around how to apply the federal election laws to the local entities who get money from the national parties and whose activity can provide overlapping benefit to presidential and congressional candidates. `` If you like a campaign that involves people at the local level, then do n't go down that slippery slope,'' of micro-regulation, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> told the commission. He warned that if the local parties are forced into complicated bookkeeping on what money is spent for federal and non-federal campaigns they will probably ignore the rules or simply bow out of campaigning. That would freeze out grassroots activity and shift to a total national TV campaign, he said. <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> and his Democratic counterpart, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Rieser </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, argued that where federal and local goals overlap, the local and state parties should not be saddled with complicated allocation formulas, but should be allowed to allocate the funds to federal and non-federal accounts in a way that best suits their situation. No matter how stringent the rules, the <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> wo n't be able to accomplish complete fairness, <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> said. `` You draw up the rules. I get paid to manipulate them,'' he said. `` Whatever you do is going to be maniplated to some degree.'' <PERSON> Rieser </PERSON> denied that the <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> gives money to local and state parties only to help the presidential race. He said the party has an interest in local level politics as well. Different states have different political situations that would make it unfair to lock them into using a standard formula for how much of their activity benefits federal elections, versus local elections. For instance, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had a plethora of hotly-contested ballot initiatives and many tight legislative races on which the state and local parties invested heavily for slate mailers and get-out-the-vote activity. Other states had little state election interest and were more focused on the presidential race. The public hearing testimony was a step in <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> compliance with a federal court order that said the commission's rules were too vague on soft money, which is banned in federal elections but is permitted in many states. Soft money generally refers to union and corporate donations, as well as individual contributions in excess of the federal limit of $ 1,000. Such funds are banned in federal elections, but permitted in many states. The focus of the current <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> deliberations is how the parties should allocate funds to soft, or non-federal accounts, and to federal accounts for campaign activities that benefit both federal and non-federal candidates. Such activities include voter registration and get-out-the-vote drives as well as slate cards and administrative costs. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Wertheimer </PERSON>, president of Common Cause, a longtime critic of the system, said that both parties in 1988 `` brazenly flouted the limits imposed by federal law on the sources and amounts of permissable contributions in connection with federal elections.'' Noting that both parties had raised millions of dollars in soft money, he accused them of using the system to circumvent the limits on what they could spend for their presidential nominees by doing it through state party activity. <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rieser </PERSON> both said they knew of no examples of soft money being spent on the campaigns of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, but they acknowledged that party spending at any level inevitably helps the top of the ticket. `` That sort of activity affects all elections,'' said <PERSON> Rieser </PERSON>. `` You ca n't help a legislative candidate without helping the top of the ticket,'' said <PERSON> Braden </PERSON>. `` Everything affects everything else.'' The <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION> raised in the neighborhood of $ 70 million this year, with about $ 20 million of that in soft money, <PERSON> Braden </PERSON> said. However, those figures did not include another $ 25 million that was raised through the `` Victory'88'' program the <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION> set up in each state, with the funds going directly into state accounts rather than to the <ORGANIZATION> RNC </ORGANIZATION>. The Democrats, said <PERSON> Rieser </PERSON>, raised about $ 60 million this year, with some $ 18 million of that in soft money. Both parties had programs to court high-dollar givers who contributed sums of $ 100,000 or more. The federal system permits an individual to give no more than $ 25,000 per year in federal election contributions, including to parties and candidates. But unlimited sums can be donated to non-federal accounts.
</TEXT>
