rce in suppressing pro-independence demonstrations in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> in the last 14 months. In his speech, <PERSON> Lord </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern for human rights `` is natural and universal. We do not single out <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' He reiterated that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recognizes <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s sovereignty over <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> but pressed for greater access to the region by foreign journalists. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has not commented on the latest clash between <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> police and <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> activists, in which police on Saturday fatally shot at least two people and injured 13. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> says its rule over <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> dates to the 13th century. Tibetan activists claim their remote region was effectively independent from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for centuries before Chinese Communist troops entered in 1950.
