 A prosecutor ordered a 41-year-old Swede held in custody Thursday in the slaying of Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>, signaling what could be a major break in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s crime of the century. The man detained Wednesday is suspected of `` having murdered <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Jorgen </PERSON> <PERSON> Almblad </PERSON>, spokesman for the prosecutor's office, told <ORGANIZATION> Swedish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s strict press and libel law forbids publication of a suspect's name, but he was identified in public records as <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>. Palme, a four-term <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> prime minister who championed international peace and disarmament issues, was killed the night of Feb. 28, 1986, while walking home unguarded with his wife from a downtown movie theater. The killing jolted a nation which prides itself on orderliness and had seen little of the political violence and terrorism that plague other countries. <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON> has a history of violent crime and a previous conviction of manslaughter. He has been interrogated since he was detained Wednesday. `` The suspicions from yesterday remain,'' said <PERSON> Almblad </PERSON>. A witness identified the man as someone who waited outside the Grand Theater, where Palme had been just before he was fatally shot, the radio reported without identifying its source. It said there were discrepancies between witness accounts and the suspect's alibi. The killer followed Palme down the street after the prime minister left the theater and shot him with a .357 magnum revolver which has not been found. Before Wednesday, police were unable to produce a solid lead or a motive in the killing, despite the largest manhunt in Swedish history and a reward of $ 8 million. The investigation was marred by squabbling between police and prosecutors, and the chief detective in the case was replaced twice. Government commissions accused police of incompetence in the investigation. Thursday's move means that prosecutors feel they have enough evidence to build a case against the man and may hold him indefinitely, although his attorney may dispute the remand order in <ORGANIZATION> Stockholm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. `` There is reason to believe it will be a difficult case,'' said <PERSON> Arne </PERSON> <PERSON> Liljeros </PERSON>, the public defender assigned to the case. `` My client denies it, says it's a mistake,'' he said in a television interview. A friend of the suspect said the man was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Sweden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, an ultra-rightist group that advocates white supremacy, the national news agency <ORGANIZATION> TT </ORGANIZATION> reported. But police have not linked him with the party, the report said. `` He did n't like <LOCATION> Palme </LOCATION>, he was angry at him,'' the unidentified friend was quoted as saying. Authorities have refused to give details of their case, but Swedish police reporters were given access to the suspect's file. Reports said he had 63 convictions for various offenses and had spent the last 22 years in and out of prisons and phychiatric wards. He was convicted of fatally stabbing an alleged drug addict with a bayonet in 1970, just a few yards from the site of the Palme killing. <PERSON> Almblad </PERSON> said the suspect had been under investigation `` for a long time,'' but declined to give further details. The man had been questioned in 1986, but was not arrested because his alibi appeared sound at the time, according to TT.
