<HEAD>Department Spends $1.3 Million Sending Collider Reports to the
Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Energy Department came under criticism Thursday from an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> congressman who said the department wasted $ 1.5 million by mailing a 26-pound, 23-volume report on the superconducting super collider to 16,000 people, sometimes sending four to a family. A department spokesman, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON>, disputed the figures cited by Rep. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., saying the report actually went to about 17,000 people and cost $ 1.3 million `` This is crazy,'' said <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON>, whose district includes one of the rejected sites for the collider. `` It's just a lack of common sense.'' The document at issue is an 8,000-page environmental impact statement on possible sites for the $ 4.4 billion atom smasher in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> announced Nov. 10 that <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> would house the project, a 53-mile, underground ring of magnets which would whip proton beams together with 20 times the force of the most powerful existing atom smasher. Scientists hope to learn more about the nature of matter from studying subatomic particles created by the proton collisions. The department sent copies of the environmental statement to everyone who testified at hearings on the project or submitted written comments on any of the seven finalist sites, <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> said. `` It is government practice that both draft and final documents be made available to interested parties as part of the environmental review process,'' he explained. `` In order to comply with that process, the department mailed that document out.'' However, <PERSON> Hastert </PERSON> said an expensive mailing went far beyond the requirement that agencies keep people involved in the site-selection process. `` The law says people have to be contacted; they do n't have to send all this stuff,'' he said. `` If the department sent a letter with a reply card, maybe they'd get 1 percent that would want the report. Then, just making them available in libraries would be enough. `` Why not do that? We're scrimping to cut spending by pennies, dimes and nickles in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. They're spending almost $ 1 -LCB- million, here, when we could be using that money to build highways or feed the homeless. What a waste!'' <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> acknowledged that the mailing might alienate members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who will decide whether to appropriate money for the collider. `` I understand where the argument is coming from. I do n't know who made the ultimate decision,'' he said. `` But if we had n't distributed -LRB- the report -RRB-, we would have been criticized for that as well.
