<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top Energy Department officials will meet here with the governors of three western states Friday in an attempt to resolve an impasse over storage of radioactive wastes from nuclear weapons plants. The governors of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> said they want to hear proposals to solve the problem when they meet with <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgado </PERSON>, chief deputy to Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON>, and other regional DOE officials. The immediate problem is to find a storage site for seven boxcars of radioactive material _ and enough additional waste to fill 17 more _ sitting outside the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Flats </LOCATION> nuclear weapons plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. The other question is when the federal government will open its Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, a prototype for permanent waste storage facilities under construction in southwestern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Elmet </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Thursday the purpose of the meeting was to provide `` a chance for some straight talk between the governors and the federal government.'' But the governors said they hope federal officials will have an answer to the problem. `` I've got all the information I need. What I need now is for them to come and say, ` We have got our act together,''' Idaho Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> said at a Thursday news conference. `` They should come with a proposal that the three governors can deal with.'' Waste has been stacking up at Rocky Flats, which manufactures plutonium components for nuclear weapons, since October when <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> turned away a boxcar headed for the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> and said the state would accept no more shipments. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> said he would not open the laboaratory to additional shipments until the pilot plant is opened and <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> has outlined a plan to remove existing waste from <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Since the ban was imposed, he said, `` There has been no progress for two months, which tells me I was right to put my foot down.'' Colorado Gov. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said he would require Rocky Flats to suspend production once its temporary storage capacity is filled. <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said during a news conference Thursday that he would not consider a 90-day extension that would permit <PERSON> DOE </PERSON> to keep waste beyond the plant's capacity. `` If they do n't have a solution, they are going to have to close it by failing to act,'' <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said. `` I do not want a de facto dump here. That's why I've kept that storage in those boxcars.'' <PERSON> Romer </PERSON> said he did not expect an immediate solution to the Rocky Flats problem, but said he hoped the DOE would `` put some alternate solutions on the table.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Caviness </PERSON>, spokesman for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Garrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Carruthers </PERSON>, said his boss wanted the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> to provide a firm deadline for opening the pilot plant and an update on the progress of some $ 240 million in mitigation funds the state has been promised. Under an agreement signed between the state and <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION> eight years ago, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is to receive $ 190 million to build bypasses around major cities through which waste