<HEAD>Mystery Behind W.Va.'s $200 Million Loss Slowly Clearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A $ 200 million drop in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> investment funds are actual dollar losses, not interest, and resulted from poor sales, state treasury officials said Thursday. As jittery local governments continued to pull their money from the state investment pool, treasury officials said they sold off $ 30 million worth of securities early to satisfy a run on the investment account. In addition, Treasurer <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON> said the man in charge of investments at the time of the 1987 loss _ former Associate Treasurer <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Margolin </PERSON> _ was warned by his staff about the bad investments but did nothing to halt them. The loss was not revealed until this week, and the news has spurred a four-day run by local and county governments on the state's consolidated investment fund, in which state agencies and local governments place money for investment by the state. The local governments pulled out another $ 37 million Thursday, bringing to $ 146 million the investment fund withdrawals since Monday _ about half of what the agencies had invested. Assistant Treasurer <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Capet </PERSON> said $ 30 million worth of securities was sold at a loss to raise the funds needed to pay the local governments. The state also sold other matured securities and all its interest earnings were used to meet the demand. `` It's a day to day thing,'' <PERSON> Capet </PERSON> said. `` From the newspaper reports that I've seen and the lack of an explanation from those in charge, our money would be at risk in the account if we were to wait for an explanation,'' said <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Administrator <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ash </PERSON>, whose county commission Thursday withdrew the $ 1.6 million it had in the investment fund. <PERSON> Manchin </PERSON>, who is in cha