<TEXT>
 Palestinians, the Arab world generally and many other countries said Thursday the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision to talk with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> may bring new life to stagnant <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace negotiations. `` I could scream and cry and say, ` Happy new peaceful era, Arabs and Israelis!''' said <PERSON> Nawal </PERSON> <PERSON> Saadi </PERSON>, 44, a pharmacist whose family fled Israeli-held <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Saadi </PERSON>, one of 1.5 million Palestinians in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, wept as she said: `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has to know that <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON>, and especially Palestinians, are for peace and the wise <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision does not mean <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will be thrown into the sea. ... We want to live in peace and share the same land.'' <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Milhem </PERSON>, a former Palestinian mayor who was expelled from the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, said Wednesday's announcement was `` a great step by a great nation.'' `` One of the major roadblocks has now been removed to convening an international conference and the peaceful co-existence between all peoples and all religions and all states,'' <PERSON> Milhem </PERSON>, former mayor of <LOCATION> Halhoul </LOCATION> and a member of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>'s ruling executive committee, said in <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>. Some radical factions of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> also hailed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision. <PERSON> Kays </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Samarai </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGA