<FIRST>r w AM-YellowstoneFires     12-15 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yellowstone Fires,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Panel Recommends Temporary Halt to `Let It Burn' Policy for
Forests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal panel on Thursday recommended a temporary halt to the `` let it burn'' policy in national parks and wilderness areas to make sure everybody understands what the policy means. In a report to the secretaries of agriculture and interior, the advisory panel said current policies permitting fires to burn under predetermined conditions `` are sound, but the policies themselves need to be refined, strengthened and reaffirmed.'' Until the moratorium is lifted, fires will be put out, officials said. `` No ... natural fires are to be allowed until fire management plans meet these standards,'' the report said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Philpot </PERSON>, co-chairman of the review panel, told reporters he expected `` the moratorium would be finished by the beginning of the Western fire season, which is the middle of May.'' <PERSON> Philpot </PERSON> is a former <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> official who is now special assistant to the deputy secretary of agriculture. The secretaries of <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> appointed the committee in September after the worst fire season in history in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s Yellowstone National Park. Some 249 fires in and near the park prompted complaints from residents and their representatives in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that their communities were being ruined by smoke and the collapse of tourism. The panel reviewed fire management policy on all federal lands, not just <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>. The panel said it found that some plans did not spell out the conditions under which natural fires would be allowed to burn. Some plans also did not consider `` values at risk outside of parks and wilderness and the number of fires that can be managed at one time,'' and `` cumulative effects of drought.'' The panel's other co-chairman, <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION>, estimated that `` Twenty-five to 30 percent of the plans have some shortcomings. Some of them are minor.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contains the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contains the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which supervises many wilderness areas and manages much national forest land adjacent to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. Interior's <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> also manage affected lands. The agencies insist they do n't have `` let it burn'' policies but rather `` let it burn if it meets our criteria'' policies. The report said the agencies reject as `` impractical and unprofessional'' the practice that fires can be allowed to burn free of conditions laid down in advance or appropriate suppression action. It said some employees essentially had advocated that policy as long as fire did n't escape the agency's land. The report said <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> and Agriculture agencies should make sure that fire management plans conform to departmental policies, that employees understand the policies, that everybody is using a common vocabulary and that agencies have agreed beforehand what to do if fires threaten to move across administrative boundaries. <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said his agency had had the report for 24 hours, and would be submitting comments to the two secretaries. `` I do n't see it as a major shift,'' <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON> said. `` It's clear we'll do more around developed areas'' in deliberately set fires to clear firebreaks or other techniques. The report, which will remain open for public comment for 60 days, recommended more research on when deliberately set fires can be used and how to use them in lodgepole pine forests, the dominant kind in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>. Many people interviewed said this technique should be available for all federal land, though it has been little used in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> and practically never in lodgepole because of the difficulty of controlling it. The fires in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> were particularly intense because of more than a century's buildup of dead trees and other matter on the forest floor. `` There is little agreement on whether management objectives can be achieved through planned ignitions when they result in high intensity crown fire,'' the report said. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Linenesch </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said he saw no reason why all parks should be barred from letting fires burn until every management plan had been approved. `` The lesson of the summer is that you can not choreograph nature,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of the association.
