<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Official's House Attacked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The house of the second-ranking official in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> was attacked with grenades last month, the embassy reported Thursday. Neither <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dlouhy </PERSON>, the deputy chief of mission, nor any of his family members or domestic employees was injured in the Nov. 25 nighttime attack. Embassy spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that men traveling in two cars through the affluent neighborhood of <PERSON> Maquilishuat </PERSON> threw several grenades and that two landed at the wall surrounding <PERSON> Dlouhy </PERSON>'s house. <PERSON> McManus </PERSON> said the two grenades caused some material damage, but no injuries. Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said one of the explosives bounced off the top of the wall into the yard. A woman was wounded by shrapnel from another grenade thrown farther down the road, according to newspaper reports published in the days after the attack. Those reports did not mention the attack on <PERSON> Dlouhy </PERSON>'s home. No group claimed responsibility for the Maquilishuat attack. Because other grenades were thrown at other homes, it was unclear if the attackers considered <PERSON> Dlouhy </PERSON>'s house their specific target. Four days after the attack, leftist guerrillas briefly took over two <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> radio stations to broadcast a statement saying <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> officials and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> buildings were considered `` legitimate targets'' in the 9-year-old civil war. The centrist government's war effort is funded by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The guerrillas, on their clandestine radio station, previously made similar statements. T