<HEAD>Israel Reacts With Shock and Dismay</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 20 grafs UPDATING with Shamir aide saying dialogue
doomed to collapse, report that Shamir considering steps to make
U.S. move fade, more Pickering quotes. PICK up 17th pvs, `Shamir,
the...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli leaders responded with anger and dismay Thursday to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> declaration that it will talk with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, a stunning reversal of policy to which they were given no time to object. Some Israelis were left with a sense of betrayal by the way the announcement was handled. Others said the dialogue with the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> is doomed to collapse. `` We believe that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will discover very soon the true face of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, and will realize that it can not be a partner for negotiations and peace,'' said <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON>, spokesman for Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. According to the daily <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was considering a unilateral Israeli step `` that will make the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision fade.'' The initiative amounted to granting a limited self-rule to 1.5 million Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied lands, <ORGANIZATION> Haaretz </ORGANIZATION> said in a front-page report in its Friday editions. The daily Hadashot described <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s decision as `` the most painful diplomatic slap in the face that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has received since its establishment. We have been left alone to face the entire world.'' Israeli officials said they were notified only 30 minutes before Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> made the announcement, which allowed no time for an attempt to dissuade the Americans. Analysts said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will face mounting pressure for a favorable response to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and delay could endanger relations with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, which is its main ally and provides $ 3 billion a year in aid. If <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> talks with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> succeed, pressure would grow for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to accept a U.N.-sponsored peace conference, which many Israelis see as a forum for demanding unreasonable concessions from the Jewish state. A conference probably would consider such issues as the Israeli settlements that dot the occupied territories, return of the territories, the status of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and the central question of an independent Palestinian state. An example of what <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> considers unreasonable was a provision in a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> resolution passed Thursday for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervision of the occupied territories and <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has declared its capital. Such right-wing leaders as <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Modai </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was prepared to take the heat. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants to speak to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, but this does n't require us to speak with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Modai </PERSON> said `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can advise us and even pressure us here and there, but we have to know how to withstand the pressures.'' Palestinians called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> decision a victory of their year-old uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, in which more than 320 Palestinians and 13 Israelis have been killed. <PERSON> Yossi </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben-Aharon </PERSON>, a senior aide to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, told foreign reporters there could be no solutions to Palestinian problems without <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` They are still where they were in the camps,'' he said. `` We are still running the show. Their lot ... has not changed by this American move. The agent to bring about change is <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and nothing can be done by bypassing <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> sent an explanatory message to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, the leaders of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s caretaker government. A text released by Israeli officials said: `` I know how sensitive an issue this is for you and the people of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The dialogue that is about to be launched is not an end in itself. It must focus on the core issue of negotiations to end the <LOCATION> Arafat-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> passed on oral assurances that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was not recognizing <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> claims to an independent state. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> army radio called <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s talk with <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> `` a hard and unpleasant one.'' <PERSON> Pickering </PERSON> said ties with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> are `` stronger than ever,'' but he said Israelis and Palestinians must make difficult concessions for peace. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, made no comment Thursday, but <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON> said: `` We regret this <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> decision, very much.'' He said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would not reconsider its refusal to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>, which it calls a terrorist organization. Dozens of Jewish settlers from the territories began