<HEAD>New Laws Would Ban Religious Discrimination In Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government proposed new laws Thursday to prevent employers in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> from discriminating on the basis of religion, but said threats of disinvestment could only produce greater misery. `` I have made absolutely clear ... that there is to be no discrimination of any sort in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> Secretary <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s top official in the province. The bill, whose passage is assured because of the governing Conservatives' huge majority in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, would force companies to report regularly on how many Catholics and Protestants they employ. It would order them if necessary to change their employment practices and levy fines of up to $ 55,000 on employers who do n't. The measures, due to take effect next summer, stopped short of imposing hiring quotas for the 40 percent <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> minority, but they mark the toughest attempt to end job discrimination in the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> province. Despite longtime bans on overt religious discrimination in jobs, <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> unemployment runs at 17 percent, 2 -LCB- times the Protestant rate. The new moves appear to have been spurred partly by threats of disinvestment from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Eight American states have endorsed fair employment principles put forward in 1984 by the late Irish statesman <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> MacBride </PERSON>. He called for ending investment in companies in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> accused of religious bias. The disinvestment lobby is headed by Irish-American legislators and pressure groups. American investment accounts for nearly 14 percent of the jobs in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. `` There is absolutely no way in which this legislation is designed to see Protestants being dismissed for Catholics to take their place,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> told reporters. `` This is about recruitment ... seeing that there is equality of opportunity.'' He said the only way to improve employment opportunities for Catholics was to create more jobs, and he called the disinvestment program in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` a very negative campaign.'' `` We're getting more jobs into <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and that combined with effective legislation is the real hope for Catholics of a fairer situation,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` There is no hope for Catholics in any policy that leads to disinvestment in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, which leads to greater misery for all.'' More than 2,700 people have been killed since political and sectarian violence broke out in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> in 1969 after several years of civil rights campaigning by <PERSON> Catholics </PERSON>. Under the new laws, all companies with more than 25 employees _ and later with 10 or more _ will have to submit reports at least once every three years on the religious composition of the work force to a new body, the Fair Employment Commission. Failure to submit a report or comply with the commission will be a criminal offense, carrying a fine of up to $ 55,000. The laws would also ban `` indirect discrimination'' in hiring practices, such as getting workers to find new workers or taking recruits from a single school. Nearly all Catholic and <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> children are educated separately. Public and private companies with more than 250 employees also will have to monitor their job applications as well as the composition of their work force.
