e he was illiterate, poor and black. `` We know what racism was in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in 1968 because of this case. Let's find out what it is in 19 and 88. This case is going to do it,'' said <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>. They based their petition on three claims: _ The knowing use of perjury from the sheriff regarding an insurance policy <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> supposedly purchased for the seven children, and from two former cellmates of <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>'s who said he had confessed to the crime One has since recanted that statement. _ Prosecutors suppressed evidence that would have shown <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> had not yet purchased the insurance on the children _ Newly discovered evidence; former <ORGANIZATION> Arcadia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> says he believes <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> was framed by the sheriff, and affidavits from nursing assistants that <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reese </PERSON> has told them she fed the poison to the children <PERSON> Cline </PERSON> did not return a telephone message left at his home. There was no answer Thursday night at the office of State Attorney <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON>, who won <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>'s conviction in 1968. <PERSON> Schaub </PERSON> leaves office next month.
