<HEAD>Jurors Hear Sounds Blasted At Polygamist Clan</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS 3 grafs on women given misdemeanor citation for
unwittingly bringing weapon to trial; no pick up.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The piercing sounds blasted at a family's farm during a 13-day police siege were demonstrated Thursday at the trial of three polygamist clan members charged with a law officer's Jurors showed little reaction as noises used in the psychological assault ranging from an air-raid type siren to a sound resembling a stuck car horn were played from two 100-watt speakers about 60 yards away from the Summit County Courthouse. The demonstration came in the ninth day of the trial of clan patriarch <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, his brother <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> and brother-in-law <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Singer </PERSON>. All are charged with second-degree murder in the Jan. 28 death of Corrections Lt. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>. House was shot and killed as he directed attack dogs toward the Swapp brothers during an arrest attempt. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON>, who precipitated the standoff when he bombed a Mormon chapel in nearby <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION> on Jan. 16, was seriously wounded during the same shootout. Judge <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> cautioned jurors that the demonstration was only to illustrate methods used to rob clan members of sleep in hopes of speeding their surrender, and that they were not exact duplications. Defense attorneys have contended that loud, piercing electronic noises, low-flying aircraft, flares and banks of brilliant lights used by authorities in an effort to exhaust the 15 barricaded clan members, including nine children, actually escalated tensions during the siege. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Landau </PERSON>, a psychologist called by the defense, testified that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>'s use of the loudspeaker may have caused anxiety, stress, irritability and reduced reasoning ability among clan members during the standoff. Earlier testimony indicated the loudspeakers were used irregularly during the final days of the standoff, and that they were repeatedly shot out or torn down by clan members. <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> said the noises were a torture and they put pillows on the children's heads in an attempt to block the sound. He said he was compelled to shoot out or tear down the speakers to stop `` the crazy noise from hell.'' Also on Wednesday, <PERSON> Addam </PERSON> <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> testified that neither he nor any other member of his family deliberately fired at officers during the firefight that ended the siege by 100 law officers. He said once the siege began, none of the family felt they could trust anything the authorities said. <PERSON> Swapp </PERSON> said he never fired at anyone during the siege and felt of killing, `` it's murder, it's wrong.'' Asked who should atone for the slaying, he said, `` that was an accident.'' Prosecutors contend and defense attorneys concede the wheelchair-bound Singer fired the fatal bullet, but Singer says he was aiming at the dogs, not House. In a related development, <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, a friend of the Swapps, was issued a misdemeanor citation charging her with illegally carrying a concealed weapon after she unwittingly brought a gun to the proceedings, officers said. <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, 36, had handed her purse to a deputy stationed at a metal detector and told him the gun was inside. She later explained to officers that she had left her purse in her car during the morning session and had retrieved it after lunch, forgetting that the weapon was inside, said Detective Sgt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON>. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> barred Foster from the courtroom for the remainder of the trial, and she was ordered to appear Tuesday in 3rd <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. The incident went virtually unnoticed in the courtroom.
