<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fonmer deacon of a faith-healing sect was sentenced to 41 months in prison Thursday for failing to seek medical help for his dying, diabetic son. <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, 43, who was convicted in October of first-degree manslaughter in the death of his son, <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON>, was a deacon in a nameless Christian fellowship that followed a literal translation of the Bible, distrusted conventional medicine, and practiced strict discipline of members. <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, 10, died of complications related to juvenile diabetes at his parent's <LOCATION> Mead </LOCATION> home Dec. 20, 1987, the day after he was spanked by his father and church founder <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON> during a faith-healing session. `` In 15 years as a judge, nothing has bothered me more than this trial, this sentencing,'' <ORGANIZATION> Spokane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> said before handing down the sentence to a grim-faced <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>. In brief remarks prior to sentencing, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> told <PERSON> Schultheis </PERSON> he loved his son and asked for mercy so that he could remain with his shattered family, especially an 8-year-old son who is in counseling. During an hour-long plea for leniency, defense attorney <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Peven </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> was under the influence of <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON> and former <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> pastor <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>. Drawing parallels to the followers of the Rev. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> who committed mass suicide in <LOCATION> Guyana </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Peven </PERSON> argued that normally intelligent people can be seduced by evil people who subvert <PERSON