<DATELINE>YEREVAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite a Soviet vow to continue searching for survivors of the Armenian earthquake, foreign rescue teams that worked in <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION> said they were told to stop digging so the town can be bulldozed. Sixty survivors were discovered in the earthquake's ruins Wednesday, eight days after the quake rattled the southern <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> region, leaving an estimated 55,000 people dead and 500,000 homeless. Search teams with tracker dogs from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> told a <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Globe </ORGANIZATION> and Mail reporter that they had been ordered out of <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>, a town of 25,000 people nearly totally destroyed by the quake. They said Soviet authorities said they were preparing to blast the ruins and bulldoze the city to prevent decomposing bodies from starting an epidemic.
