<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Earth is `` under siege by the invasion of human products that destroy its atmosphere, its water, its flora and fauna,'' says a conference of 40 scientists and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> theologians. Citing damage to the ozone layer, degrading of land, pollution of water below and above ground, toxic materials injected into the air, deforestation intensifying droughts and floods, the conference says: `` God's earth faces a crisis ... As the recognition of God's land onwership gave way to the notion of human ownership, land became a commodity ... Humans began treating the land as a resource rather than a created partner.'' The conference was jointly sponsored last month by the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christianity </ORGANIZATION> and Ecology and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, embracing 161 Reformed and Presbyterian denominations totaling about 70 million members.
