<FIRST>a a AM-PuebloCrew Adv23   12-15 1125</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pueblo Crew, Adv23,1166</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Crewmen of Seized Ship Have Lost No Bitterness</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two days before Christmas 20 years ago, the captive crewmen of the spy ship USS Pueblo crossed the `` Bridge of No Return'' to freedom, but they still have n't put their bitterness behind them. `` I thought they would shoot me in the back,'' recalled crew member <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON>. `` I did n't believe it until I was on the other side.'' `` I felt like I had just come back from the dead,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, captain of the ship that had been seized on the high seas by <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, the first such taking of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warship in a century and a half. The crewmembers remain angry at the American military's failure to protect the lightly armed vessel or to come to its aid. `` There were so many people at the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION> level on down who were n't paying attention to their damn job,'' said <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>. `` They would have greatly preferred for the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> to have done us in completely.'' Instead, one crewman was killed in the attack and the 82 others were subjected to 11 months of brutal captivity. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> at that time had enormous military forces in the western <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> within 5 minutes flying time of us,'' <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, now 61, said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Poway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` I would have thought something could be mustered to come to our aid. But everybody just forgot we were there.'' <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON>, 44, of <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, was a civilian oceanographer employed by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and assigned to the <LOCATION> Pueblo </LOCATION> to provide a cover for the ship's real mission of collecting electronic intelligence. He believes the capture demonstrated an American naivete about the world. Conducting espionage off the North Korean coast was not the same as running similar missions off the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, he said. `` The North Koreans did n't play by the rules.'' Throughout the attack, seizure and early days of captivity, <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said, `` We expected someone to come over the horizon to rescue us.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chicca </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> sergeant who worked as a Korean linguist on the Pueblo, said he still finds it difficult to believe there was no retaliation. `` I would lay the blame on every military commander who was in helping range and did n't come,'' said <PERSON> Chicca </PERSON>, 44, in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Bonita </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. Retired Adm. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyland </PERSON>, commander in chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> at the time, said it is difficult to provide protection for a spy ship. Writing in this fall's issue of Naval History magazine, <PERSON> Hyland </PERSON> said, `` There is n't any way you can do anything for an intellgience-gathering ship unless you want to accompany it with a destroyer, which would defeat the purpose.'' <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, who retired from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in 1973 after 27 -LCB- years of service, said the lack of preparedness that permitted the Pueblo humiliation persists in the military today. Pointing to the failed mission to rescue American hostages in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in 1980 and the terrorist bombing that killed more than 200 Marines in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> in 1983, he said, `` As the years have passed I have learned of the incredible disarray our defenses are in.'' The weather was clear and cold on Jan. 23, 1968, as the <LOCATION> Pueblo </LOCATION> lolled about 15 miles off the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> coast _ three miles outside the communist nation's territorial waters. <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> was taking water-temperature measurements as four North Korean torpedo boats and two subchasers, all heavily armed, approached the 176-foot Pueblo around noon. `` They circled around and had their guns trained on us,'' <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said. A subchaser raised a signal flag asking the Pueblo's nationality, and <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> ordered the hoisting of the American flag. When the subchaser ordered the <LOCATION> Pueblo </LOCATION> to follow it, the American ship began to move away. One of the boats suddenly opened fire on the Pueblo with its 57mm cannon, slightly wounding <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> and another crewman. A later salvo killed Fireman <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodges </PERSON> and wounded <LOCATION> Chicca </LOCATION> and several others. <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> ordered the Pueblo stopped and stalled for time as crewmen radioed for help and frantically destroyed classified documents. Shortly after 2 p.m. the Pueblo, which never fired a shot from its .50 - caliber machine guns, was boarded by about 10 North Korean soldiers clad in olive green quilted jackets and carrying submachine The Pueblo became the first <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> warship captured since 1807 when a British ship forced the <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> to surrender off the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> capes. After the North Koreans failed to extract `` confessions'' from the men during initial interrogations, the torture and beatings began. `` They wanted us to say we were inside their territorial waters and spying on them,'' <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said. `` You were helpless, and after a while, hopeless.'' The worst part of the imprisonment was `` hell week,'' which came late in the crew's captivity, <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said. `` They had me kneel down and took a hammer handle and started pounding my head. They put a board on the back of my knees and jumped up and down on it. `` After it stopped they came in and gave me a pail of water and a brush to wash my blood off the floor and stucco walls,'' <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> said he was `` kicked into unconsciousness. That I endured a few times.'' <PERSON> Chicca </PERSON>'s nose was broken several times. `` They did n't like <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. Freedom finally came on Dec. 23 at the bridge separating <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ but only after <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials signed an apology that they immediately repudiated. A <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> court of inquiry recommended a court-martial for <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON>, who violated the hallowed <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> code of `` do n't give up the ship.'' That finding was reduced to a letter of reprimand by the commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION>. The court of inquiry also recommended a reprimand for the admiral responsible for ensuring the Pueblo's safety. Secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chafee </PERSON> overturned the panel's recommendations on the day they were made public, saying the Pueblo crew had suffered enough `` If he -LRB- <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> -RRB- had n't surrendered they would have blown the ship out of the water,'' <PERSON> Iredale </PERSON> said. `` It would be suicide.'' <PERSON> Bucher </PERSON> said he was under orders to observe the North Koreans but `` not to incite them.'' Still, he said in some ways he feels personally responsible. `` Whatever I was unable to do are the things I feel worst about,'' he said. `` If I had a way to destroy the ship, we would have abandoned it and blown it up. I tried to get cans of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION> before we sailed, but the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said they did n't have any.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Dec. 23</NOTE>
