<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:King Adv21   12-15 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: King, Adv21,0697</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Dec 21 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>B.B. Takes Lucille From the Blues to U2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For years, playing the blues was a sure way to get them, says guitar great B.B. King. `` That has hit me pretty hard, that the blues were not popular for a long time,'' said King, recalling the days in the 1960s and'70s when he was more popular in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> than at home. `` It was like being black twice. But I kept working hard, kept practicing, kept playing.'' He and `` <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON>,'' his guitar, are still playing. After overcoming prejudice both racial and musical, King is now revered as a blues giant; he's just released his 52nd blues album, and he almost steals the show from U2 in their concert movie, `` U2 Rattle and Hum.'' `` I was in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, and -LRB- U2 lead singer -RRB- <PERSON> Bono </PERSON> came by,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said recently about their collaboration. `` I'd always admired him and the group, and we talked about songwriting. I told him to think of me when he was writing, and he said, ` OK, I'll do it.''' The result, `` When Love Comes to Town,'' features King swapping vocals with <PERSON> Bono </PERSON> and playing his distinctive lead guitar over U2's backbeat _ a merging of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> delta and the <ORGANIZATION> Emerald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Isle </ORGANIZATION> recorded at the renowned <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. King, 63, was born in <LOCATION> Indianola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and took up the guitar at an early He started out playing and singing gospel, but soon began taking requests from churchgoers for more secular music. Making the guitar a career, he recalled, was a financial decision easily reached. `` I made $ 22.50 on a plantation driving a tractor all week. Playing guitar on a Saturday night I made $ 25 _ understand, that's for one evening,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said `` That's when I decided.'' King moved to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> after World War II, dubbing himself the `` <ORGANIZATION> Beale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blues </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boy </ORGANIZATION>'' _ later shortened to B.B. In 1951, he scored his first hit with `` 3 O'Clock Blues'' and his career was off and running. But during the British Invasion of the'60s and the disco craze of the'70s, King and his music slipped into the background. Despite the lack of acclaim, King never considered playing any other music. `` No, I did n't even think about it; I never felt that way,'' he said. `` I felt bad, I felt ridiculed, looked down upon for doing this kind of music. I wished it was different, but everything I play is bluesy.'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said his instantly-recognizable guitar style was developed more because of his ears than his hands: `` I ca n't hear lows, so I would turn the treble up. That's how it started.'' But it's evolving to this day, he said before a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> appearance at the <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> and Hedges Blues Festival to benefit the homeless. `` It's always changing. I'm influenced by everything. There are young people today who come up and say they idolize me _ I learn from them. It's a round-robin.'' Another thing that has the veteran musician smiling is the number of current artists who are acknowledging the blues `` are the mother of all music.'' King cited <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cray </PERSON> as a particular favorite. Then he named another musician who loved the blues: the late <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>. `` I remember once an interviewer asked <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON> what he'd like to being doing. And he said, ` Playing guitar, playing the blues like B.B. King,''' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said. `` He never knew what that meant to me. It feels good to hear people talk like that.'' Despite his advancing years, <PERSON> King </PERSON> keeps an active schedule; he estimates spending 300 days a year on the road. And he has no intention of hanging up `` Lucille'' any time in the near future. `` When the great creator says it's enough, that's when I'll stop,'' said King `` What else would I do? It's like Count Basie told me one time: My friends are around the world. If I stopped playing, how could I see them all?''
