<FIRST>a a AM-TreatmentforSale Adv19-2Takes   12-15 1075</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treatment for Sale, Adv19-2 Takes,1110</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Maverick Researcher's Approach to Developing Cancer Drugs Is
Faltering</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A maverick researcher's efforts to speed tests on unproven cancer therapies by selling them to any patients willing to pay is faltering. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>, founder of <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has so far been unable to show that the treatments, which cost as much as $ 24,000, can prolong lives or reduce the severity of symptoms. Although patients stoutly defend their right to seek his experimental help, <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is failing to attract enough patients to make a profit. What is more, he has been attacked by doctors and scientists who say it's unethical, and possibly dangerous, to sell treatments not yet shown to work. Dr. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Relman </PERSON>, editor of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, says patients who go to <LOCATION> Oldham </LOCATION> `` are people desperate with fear. They're dying of cancer. And they're encouraged to believe there might be some hope. It's cruel deception. It's commercial exploitation of a tragedy. I think it's totally immoral.'' Biotherapeutics was the first profit-making enterprise to take advantage of government reluctance to allow sales of most experimental drugs until they've been throroughly tested for safety and effectiveness. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>'s daring decision to sell such unproven treatments to the public, and risk federal closure, has put <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION> in the midst of a debate over what the government might do to speed delivery of new drugs to dying patients. The outcome is vitally important to anyone who will be touched by cancer, AIDS, heart disease or any other incurable ailment. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is selling what are called immune therapies. They have been widely touted as an important fourth weapon against cancer, augmenting the triple arsenal of chemotherapy, radiation and surgery that cure only about half of the almost 1 million Americans diagnosed with cancer each year. Immune therapies, sometimes called biological therapies, are intended to provoke the body's immune system to destroy invading cancer cells. The hope _ and so far it remains little more than a hope _ is that the therapies may attack tumors impervious to conventional therapies. Another potential advantage is that the immune system may target cancer cells more accurately than conventional treatments, thus producing fewer of the harmful side effects often associated with chemotherapy and radiation. Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, who has done much of the pioneering work in biological therapy, calls this `` the dawn of a new approach to treating cancer.'' `` I've now had almost 20 patients with widespread, metastatic cancer that's disappeared,'' <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> Rosenberg </PERSON> is, however, a sharp critic of <LOCATION> Oldham </LOCATION>. He asserts that biological therapy is not ready for widespread use. `` The worst thing we can do is raise false expectations,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is located in a squat, modern, red-brick building just outside <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>, an antebellum town 18 miles south of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> with a picturesque square frequently sought out by moviemakers. The building's Y-shaped entrance resembles an antibody molecule, a reminder of the company's use of cancer antibodies in some treatments. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>, the company's dominant presence, is a well-known researcher with more than 300 papers to his credit. Among his accomplishments, he lists the discovery of certain white blood cells called natural killer cells, which help defend the body against disease. He began his research career at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. He left in 1975 to establish the cancer program at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> but returned to the cancer institute in 1980 to initiate research on biological therapy for cancer. He left the institute again in 1984, this time to set up Biotherapeutics, which focuses almost exclusively on the use of biological anti-cancer agents. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is a tough, combative man. He bristles at criticism of Biotherapeutics and seeks opportunities to defend himself and his enterprise. If cancer patients want the treatments he offers _ whether those treatments work or not _ then the patients ought to get them, <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> says. `` Where does society come off saying you ca n't have it?'' he argued. For more than three years, <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> has sidestepped federal regulations on the sale of experimental treatments by claiming to be in the business of patient-funded research. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> says he is not selling treatment. He says he's recruiting patients to serve as subjects in cancer research _ and to pay for the privilege. He says what he is doing is no different from what the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> is doing, except for the source of the funding. The cancer institute gets its money from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION> gets its money from patients. But is Oldham selling research? Interviews with patients, <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> and other company officials suggest that people are coming to Biotherapeutics not to contribute to a research effort, but to try to save their lives. Here is the wording on a poster outside his office: `` If you had cancer, and traditional treatments were n't effective, what would you do? Give up? Or fight, pursuing every option? ... When standard therapies fail, we offer patients a scientifically valid option.'' Ask <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>'s patients why they have come to him, and it's clear they're seeking treatment _ not a chance to be guinea pigs. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> was recently treated by <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> for colon cancer. His doctor in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, had told him he could do nothing more for him. Why had <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> come to <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>? `` You do n't have any alternative if you want to fight it,'' he said in an interview in his hospital room. `` Eventually I will die, but at least I'll give it a shot. ... I think Biotherapeutics charging -LRB- for experimental treatments -RRB- is better than not giving people a shot at it.'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, 60, said he hoped his case would help <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> learn something that might help others, but that was n't why he was there. A salesman for a computer systems development company, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said he and his wife paid for his treatment with money from their retirement account. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> knows the Biotherapeutics treatment is a long shot. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> explained that well. And he believes that, ideally, experimental treatments should n't be commercialized, as <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>'s are. `` But the government is n't doing anything,'' <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said. `` You call the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and ask about colon cancer and you get a tape.'' You call <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>, and if you are have the strength left and the money, you get treated.
