<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Dec. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>FRANKLIN: get treated.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 The two principal therapies <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is using are monoclonal antibodies and adoptive immunotherapy. Monoclonal antibodies are protective proteins produced in mice that have been injected with human cancer cells. Such antibodies could, theoretically, attack and destroy tumors or could be used to carry cancer-killing drugs directly to tumors. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is selling a monoclonal antibody treatment for $ 24,000. Does it work? `` It's too soon to tell,'' he said. Adoptive immunotherapy involves taking immune cells from cancer patients, stimulating the cells with a drug called interleukin-2, and re-injecting them in the hope the cells will attack the patients' tumors. The cells are called lymphokine-activated killer cells, or LAKs. This treatment has been shown to be of some help in fighting melanoma and kidney cancer. Ten percent of such patients show a dramatic reduction in tumor size, but whether the treatments will improve or extend their lives is not yet known. `` It's probably helping some people,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Chabner </PERSON>, director of the cancer treatment program at the National Cancer Institute. Kidney and other urinary cancers will strike 22,500 Americans this year and melanoma will strike 27,300, says the American Cancer Society. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is selling adoptive immunotherapy for 50 percent off the regular price of $ 19,400. Does it work? `` It's too early to tell,'' he said. Many of <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON>'s critics have questioned why the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has n't acted to stop Biotherapeutics. Charging for experimental treatments is usually prohibited by the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, according to Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Temple </PERSON>, a director in the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s drug evaluation office. `` We in general do n't think people should be charged for investigational drugs,'' he said. `` They have n't been shown to work yet; it's not fair.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> says it has n't made a decision yet on Biotherapeutics. Many doctors outside the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> say the agency is knotted in sharp internal debate. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Barton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutt </PERSON>, formerly the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s chief counsel and now a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer, put the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s fundamental dilemma this way: `` If someone is desperately ill and has no other hope, should the government tell them what they can take? Balanced against that, if the patient is desperately ill and has no hope, should there be protection against them being defrauded?'' An additional complication is that <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION>' company structure makes it difficult for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to act. Biotherapeutics does not send its drugs across state lines. It has hospital affiliates scattered across the country, but each hospital has a nearby laboratory that produces drugs according to the Biotherapeutics recipe. Dr. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlington </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s division of biological investigational new drugs, said that limits the agency's ability to act `` With intrastate activities, there is debate over the extent of our jurisdiction,'' he said. While the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> ponders its moves, the ethical debate over <LOCATION> Oldham </LOCATION>'s activities continues Dr. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Grodin </PERSON>, a pediatrician and director of the medical ethics program at <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, says <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> clearly has conflicting interests. As a doctor, he should be helping patients. As a researcher, he should be trying to advance general knowledge, not to save dying patients. And as a businessman, he should be trying to keep his company afloat. `` It seems to me that the patient ca n't sort that out, even if the researcher can,'' said <PERSON> Grodin </PERSON>. The immediate concern of Biotherapeutics is not, however, in resolving these ethical tangles but in curing the company's financial ills In the most recent fiscal year, <ORGANIZATION> Biotherapeutics </ORGANIZATION> lost almost $ 10 million of the $ 40 million stake it raised to go into business. It treated 400 patients, and, said <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Berneman </PERSON>, the company's president, `` the expectations were that that would have been higher. He would n't say exactly what the company had hoped for. If management ca n't turn its troubled finances around, the company wo n't survive beyond 1990, said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, its chief financial officer. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> added, however, that he had little doubt that the company would make it. It has already taken some drastic steps. The price of its most expensive product _ the monoclonal antibody treatment _ has been cut from $ 35,000 to $ 24,000. Adoptive immunotherapy is on sale for $ 9,700. The company hopes to persuade patients' insurance companies to come up with the rest, although insurance companies as a rule do not reimburse patients for experimental treatments. Biotherapeutics hopes the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> will approve interleukin-2 next year for use against kidney cancer and melanoma. <PERSON> Berneman </PERSON> thinks insurance companies will then reimburse the costs of adoptive immunotherapy. <PERSON> Oldham </PERSON> is determined to press on against whatever odds. `` Some of our critics would legislate and regulate against us being available,'' he said. `` And that is wrong.''
