<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>HAVANA: 50 percent.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 For millions of Cubans, <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> remains an inspirational figure. His oratorical skills are undiminished. He impresses visitors with the breadth of his interests, ranging from medicine to nuclear power. Little occurs in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> which escapes his restless gaze. Seldom has a leader of so small a country had an international impact as great as his. He can claim partial credit for the agreement under which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> will grant <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s last colony, independence and black majority rule. That was <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s price for agreeing to withdraw <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s forces from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Above all, he sees himself as the broker for the dispossessed. He constantly expresses outrage about the injustice of a world in which some countries enjoy boundless abundance while others starve _ 120,000 children every three days, a <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> and a <LOCATION> Nagasaki </LOCATION> every 72 hours, he claims. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> is proud that the infant mortality rate in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is comparable to that in some of the most developed countries. One reason <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has had difficulty developing economically is that so much of the country's resources go toward meeting basic human needs _ housing, schools and hospitals. The vast majority of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s children have the opportunity to develop their minds and bodies through <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s far-reaching educational and sports programs. On a per capita basis, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> quite possibly produces more good boxers, runners, swimmers and baseball players than any other country. While more than a million Cubans have fled the island since 1959, the revolution has rescued countless others, mostly peasants and workers, from the social and economic oblivion they endured under the previous system. Block-by-block `` defense committees'' are used to monitor the politically suspect but they also have helped make <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s streets as safe as any in the hemisphere. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> also boasts that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is drug free. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has been at the helm in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> for well over half his adult life and, at 62, he shows no sign of slowing down. If he does falter, brother <PERSON> Raul </PERSON>, 57, has been tapped as the successor. But <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON>, as he is known to his countrymen, may well be around for years to come. He has outlasted six <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents. Next month, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will become the seventh.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 25</NOTE>
