<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Mazda Builds U.S. Designed Mini-van</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto and LaserGraphic</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 15th paragraph to CORRECT spelling to two-passenger.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANN M. JOB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>For The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 About the time <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> was getting ready to introduce its minivans for the 1984 model year, <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> employees in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had their own concept for a minivan on the drawing boards. The result, the 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MPV </ORGANIZATION>, debuted in November and marks a milestone in the Japanese automaker's history. The MPV _ an aerodynamic-shaped and smartly dressed package _ is the first <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> vehicle born of an initial design that originated in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In fact, the MPV -LRB- for multipurpose vehicle -RRB- is not sold today in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION>'s home country. The vehicle, designed with American buyers in mind, is built in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> but sold only in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Sales of about 40,000 are forecast through October 1989, including about 4,000 four-wheel-drive models due out beginning in March, said spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON>. For the following 12 months, steady sales of another 40,000 are expected, he added. Early results were heartening, with <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> reporting more than 900 sold in the first three weeks the vehicles were out. `` We feel the -LRB- minivan -RRB- market is continuing to expand,'' <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said. `` Our sales need to come from the additional buyers into the market and from the domestics.'' Besides Chrysler, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> also sell small vans, though <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> outpaces all the competition in sales. The No. 3 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker has sold more than 1 million of its <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caravan </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voyager </ORGANIZATION> vans since the 1984 model year. Major Japanese automakers such as <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> also sell minivans here, but <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> MPV </ORGANIZATION> is different because it is not as box-like as the competitors. In price, however, the MPV is in the midst of all the others. <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said the base price for a two-passenger cargo van is $ 10,989, with the lowest-priced five-passenger MPV wagon at $ 12,909. The base price for a seven-passenger MPV with the standard four-cylinder engine is $ 13,759. The test vehicle had a V6 engine and topped out at just over $ 19,000. Those price ranges are comparable to the competition. The MPV has a side door that opens outward, like a regular car door, rather than a sliding side door that is standard on other vans. The MPV's side door, however, opens to a maximum 90 degrees _ greater than that on a car door. The design allows a slightly wider door opening on the vehicle than on other small vans, <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> noted. The swing-out door is lighter and easier for children to manage than some sliding doors. The MPV side door also features a bar that's easy to grab and use when manuevering around in the back. In addition, swing-out doors have greater durability and are less prone to rattles during driving, <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said. Another feature on the test MPV _ a seven-passenger model _ was a three-passenger rear bench seat with a seatback that folded down so the folded seat could be pushed upward and locked in place behind the middle bench seat. It's an unusual-looking arrangement but provides cargo space in back. On other vans, the rear seat can be unlocked from the floor and removed, but the MPV rear seat ca n't be removed unless hand tools are used first to unfasten it from the floor. That's a bit awkward and time-consuming for someone who wants to get large, long items in the van. But <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> countered that buyers may not have to remove the MPV rear seat seat at all. <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> designed the rear seat bench and the two-passenger middle seat with seatbacks that fold down backwards for a somewhat uneven, but mostly flat, bed. <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> suggested buyers just load their long items on that bed. But I do n't know that owners want long, dirty items _ such as wood _ on their upholstery. Would n't owners rather put the items on the floor as permitted in other vans? -LRB- The MPV's middle seat is removable, however, with a flip of a couple latches, if you have cargo that is not very long. -RRB- The MPV, like all vans, offered good visibility, because of its higher riding profile. Still, it handled like a car, except for some body sway around corners. The van is rear-drive, as opposed to the front-drive Chrysler products, permitting towing capabilities of up to 4,300 pounds with the optional MPV towing package. Despite the rear-drive configuration, however, the MPV has a flat floor, save for the slightly raised area under the rear bench seat where suspension coil springs are located. Probably the most enjoyable part of the MPV was the optional 3-liter V6 engine which performed flawlessly. Teamed with a four-speed automatic overdrive transmission, the engine was smooth and peppy. It's the same powerplant that's in the Mazda 929. The standard engine for the MPV is a 2.6-liter four-cylinder that's newly developed for the van, <PERSON> Aikins </PERSON> said. Another highlight of the MPV was the nicely appointed interior. Upholstery is placed on the sides of the doors, providing soft armrests, and carpeting is below on the sides of the doors, giving the impression of a nicely integrated interior. There was even a nifty pull-down two-cup holder on the side of the front passenger seat. About the only complaint was that the dashboard featured a tiny mapbox and a too-small glovebox. The van's interior was spacious, and legroom was admirable in all three seating areas _ front, middle and rear. It was relatively easy to move around inside, though obviously, you must hunch over a bit. The sloping front dashboard design gave an airy feel. Fit and finish was superb. The test vehicle had the optional, separate air conditioner for rear-seat passengers _ another nice touch. <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> says its target buyers are men, but company officials expect women to be the primary drivers. That's explained by the fact that 73 percent of the potential buyers are male, with 88 percent married. The median age is 39, 60 percent are college graduates. The MPV is new, there are no trouble index reports from Consumer Reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Job </PERSON>, former executive business editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, writes biweekly automobile reviews for The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. She has covered the automobile industry for six years.
