<HEAD>Pam Dawber Plays Wife of Stricken Football Coach</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDS: RETRANSMISSION to correct cycle designator to BC.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The story of a football coach stricken in the prime of life by <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gehrig </PERSON>'s disease is n't exactly light-hearted viewing, but <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>, who plays the coach's wife, found the movie `` happy.'' `` It's really about the human spirit at its very best,'' she said. `` I think he inspires so many people by overcoming his own incredible trauma. It's a hopeful, happy movie.'' It was soon after <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> sitcom `` My Sister <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>'' was finally dropped for good after bouncing around the schedule for two seasons that she was offered the role as <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON> in the real-life movie `` Quiet Victory,'' which <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> will air Monday, the day after Christmas. Mrs. <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON> helps her husband, <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Nouri </PERSON> -RRB-, continue his coaching career despite the disease that leaves him unable to speak or move. <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON> had held off new projects until she got final word on `` My Sister <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>,'' so the movie offer came as she was ready for something new. The series was on-again, off-again on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> until April. `` We all thought we were going back to work on the <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. `` Tribune Entertainment was nearly ready to make 44 new shows. Then it fell through. Too bad. It was a good show. But it was the victim of network politics. `` They wanted our Monday night time slot for a new show, ` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s Place. So they ended up killing two shows. ` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s Place' never should have been on at 8 o'clock. It was a more sophisticated show.'' `` My Sister <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>'' was moved to Saturday night its second year, but was soon taken off the air. It returned briefly in April as part of CBS' ill-fated attempt to program sitcoms on Tuesday. April was n't all bad for <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>. She and husband <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> had their son, <PERSON> Sean </PERSON>. For `` Quiet Victory,'' she packed up her new baby and spent several weeks filming on Folly Beach, on one of the sea islands off <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The Wedemeyers live in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gatos </LOCATION>, which is south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, but it was too expensive to film there. `` So, we went to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, which has palm trees, old houses and beaches,'' she said. <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON> was 30 when he learned he had amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, called <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Gehrig </PERSON>'s disease after the famous <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> first baseman who was also stricken. A former star quarterback at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON> was coaching the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gatos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildcats </ORGANIZATION> and teaching mathematics. He was married to his high school sweetheart, <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON>, a former cheerleader. He's a native of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, where he was known as `` Kalekauwila,'' God of Lightning. His brother is <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Wedemeyer </PERSON>, another football star, who played Detective <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukela </PERSON> for eight years on `` <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> Five-0.'' `` Charlie is completely immobile,'' said <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>. `` He can move his lips. He has a portable breathing apparatus and a feeding tube and sometimes gets around in a golf cart. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> reads his lips and relays his coaching commands to the team. ... `` He's a regal, charismatic man. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON>'s kept him alive through her attitude. They both have a wonderful sense of humor. She's a terribly selfless woman. <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> in a way is the cheerleader for <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gatos </LOCATION>. The community has done so much for them and with them.'' The movie was directed by <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Campanella </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, whose father played for the <ORGANIZATION> Brooklyn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dodgers </ORGANIZATION> until an automobile accident left him an invalid. Now that the movie is completed, <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>, who gained fame as <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>' foil on `` Mork and <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON>,'' is `` shopping around'' for a new comedy series. A sitcom offers `` the most reasonble schedule,'' she said. `` I do n't want my son dragged around while I do more movies. I want the industry to know that I'm available.'' <PERSON> Dawber </PERSON>, who has sung in many musicals, including `` Pirates of Penzance'' on Broadway, planned to audition for the role of <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> production of `` Phantom of the Opera.'' She said she would have to audition without benefit of having seen the play, since she was unable to get tickets to the show in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.
