<HEAD>The Years, in Its Own Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 It was a year of election triumph and defeat in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and of glimmerings of peace around the world. The news stories of 1988 here are told in the words of those who made the news:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` We totally and absolutely renounce all forms of terrorism.'' _ <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, Dec. 14, in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. `` I have authorized the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to enter into a substantive dialogue with <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> representatives.'' _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a statement issued just hours after <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> spoke.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` I never thought I would see the day the Soviets were involved with us here.'' _ <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Behne </PERSON>, test director from <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet scientists prepared joint verification Aug. 15 of a nuclear test blast in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` It is now quite clear that building up military power makes no country omnipotent. What's more, one-sided reliance on military power ultimately weakens other components of national security.'' _ Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announcing Soviet troop reductions during his speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 7.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The suspect aircraft was outside the prescribed commercial air corridor. More importantly, the aircraft headed directly for <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> on a constant bearing at high speed. ... We do have indications that the people on the ship were led to believe ... that the aircraft was ... decreasing in altitude as it neared the ship. ... Given the threatening flight profile and the decreasing range, the aircraft was declared hostile.'' _ Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, on July 3, after the USS Vincennes shot down Iranian airliner, killing 290 people. `` IR 655 ... was in the assigned airway ... At no time did IR 655 actually descend in altitude prior to engagement.'' _ Final investigative <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> report on the shootdown, released Aug. 19.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` I tell him every morning that worrying wo n't make any difference anyway.'' _ <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Kodat </PERSON>, on the advice she gives her husband, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON>, a farmer in <LOCATION> Morris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, whose crops withered in the worst <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drought in a half-century.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` It was a case of fry and die or jump and try.'' _ <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, 45, who leaped to safety from an explosion July 8 that ripped apart an oil rig 120 miles off <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, killing 167.
