<HEAD>Trade Deficit Shrinks, Factory Use Up, But Markets Not Pleased</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit dipped slightly in October and the nation's factories ran at their highest rate in nine years in November, the government says. Stocks and bonds fell Wednesday in reaction to the reports. Investors feared they hinted at higher inflation in the months ahead and possible moves by the nation's central bank to nudge up interest rates. The merchandise trade deficit for October fell 3.1 percent to $ 10.3 billion, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. But investors decided the improvement would not continue unless the dollar fell further to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods more competitive in world markets. That could depress stocks and bonds. In the day's other big economic report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry in November was using more of its capacity than at any time in nine years. The operating rate at factories, mines and utilities was 84.2 percent last month, up from 84.0 percent in October and the highest rate since November 1979. That raised speculation that factories were running too close to full tilt, possibly leading to shortages that would boost inflation. `` We're starting to approach levels of capacity utilization in some industries that will mean higher prices. If growth continues at this rate, we'll soon find most industries passing on higher prices and we'll see monthly increases in the inflation numbers,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berson </PERSON>, an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 9.24 points to 2,134.25 on Wednesday as declining issues outnumbered advances by about 6 to 5 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks. In the bond market, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond lost -RCB- point, or about $ 7.50 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to its price and is often an indicator of interest rate trends, climbed to 9.04 percent from 8.97 percent late Tuesday. The dollar retreated against major currencies Wednesday, hurt by what money dealers called rumors of a hike in West German interest rates and a negative market reaction to the monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade report. `` The figures came out in line with expectations, and since there's overriding bearish sentiment to the dollar, people just resumed selling it,'' said <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Yannalfo </PERSON>, a trader at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commodities futures firm <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In other economic news Wednesday: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said business inventories in October climbed at the slowest rate in five months, while sales surged a strong 1.2 percent The report suggested robust economic growth. _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said its industrial production index in November increased by 0.5 percent for the second month in a row _ Sales of U.S.-made cars and light trucks fell 11 percent in early December compared with a burst of incentive-driven sales in the same period a year earlier, domestic automakers reported <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities trader in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said improvement in the trade deficit will slow in the months ahead. He said capacity strains will make it difficult to manufacture more exports, and strong domestic demand will suck in more imports.
</TEXT>
