<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anticipation of colder weather in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> has pushed wholesale home heating oil prices sharply higher. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the January contract for heating oil rose 1.86 cents Wednesday to settle at 51.13 cents a gallon, after falling 0.93 cent on profit-taking Tuesday. Other contract months were up more than a penny. Prices were higher Monday and Friday on the arrival of sub-freezing temperatures in the Northeast. The weather remained cold on Wednesday, and parts of the region were hit with snow. <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, a senior energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>, said Wednesday's `` heating oil market ... was supported by anticipation of colder weather in the Northeast.'' Among other refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Wednesday, January unleaded gasoline, which fell 0.90 cent on Tuesday, rose 0.42 cent to settle at 43.72 cents a gallon. The January contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, settled at $ 16.37 a barrel, up 37 cents from Tuesday, when it fell 6 cents. <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON> said the markets also got a boost from reports that non-OPEC oil producers <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> would be willing to cut production if the cartel sticks to an output-slashing pact ratified last month. The 13-nation <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> agreed to keep daily crude production at 18.5 million barrels to help prop up sagging worldwide oil prices. `` Overall, the traders' sentiment seems to be changing. They're more optimistic <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> is going to cut production, and there's no sign to lead to the contrary,'' said <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>
</TEXT>
