<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar moved slightly higher in thin European trading late this morning as the market waited for a widely expected increase in a key West German interest rate in the wake of a round of interest rate increases elsewhere in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Gold prices also rose. Traders said an increase in the West German Lombard rate is likely to be matched by a rise in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate The Lombard rate is what the West German central bank charges commercial banks for supplemental borrowings in which securities are used as collateral. The discount rate is what the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> central bank charges on loans to commercial banks. There were interest rate hikes in the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Wednesday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.8312, compared with $ 1.8335 Wednesday. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Wednesday's rates, included: 1.7362 West German marks, down from 1.7365; 1.4638 Swiss francs, up from 1.4630; 5.9365 French francs, up from 5.9350; 1.9593 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9590; 1,286.00 Italian lire, up from 1,279.50; 1.2005 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1986 In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.38 yen to a closing 122.97 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 122.85 yen. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 421.40 a troy ounce, up from $ 420.75 bid late Wednesday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price also of $ 421.40 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 421.25, up from $ 420 bid late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.67 to close at a bid $ 423.05. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.21 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's $ 6.16.
