<HEAD>Stores Sue State Over Dec. 26 Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five retail stores have sued the State of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> for the right of all stores to open during normal business hours on Dec. 26 without having to get local permits. The stores are challenging state Commissioner of Labor and Industries <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>'s interpretation of a new state law on store openings the days after Christmas and New Year's. The holidays fall on Sundays this year. Snow ruled that Sunday hours will apply on Monday, Dec. 26. That means the stores can not open before noon unless they get permission from their local police chiefs, and the permits must be confirmed by the state. Snow already has said the state will confirm all local permits, but many local police chiefs have refused to grant them. The suit was filed Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Suffolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by <PERSON> Filene </PERSON>'s, <ORGANIZATION> Filene </ORGANIZATION>'s Basement, <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lechmere </ORGANIZATION>. Permits to open before noon have been granted by police chiefs in <LOCATION> Auburn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Danvers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newton </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Westborough </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Westfield </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>. Permits have been denied by chiefs in <LOCATION> Belmont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Braintree </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brockton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dedham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hyannis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Natick </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wellesley </LOCATION>. `` The retailers reluctantly decided to take this action primarily for customer-service reasons,'' said <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Dawn-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Driscoll </PERSON>. `` On the day after Christmas, customers appear early to make exchanges, to use gift certificates and to take advantage of after-Christmas sales. `` Retailers would lose a lot of customer goodwill by being open in some locations and being closed in others.'' Under state law, when some holidays, including Christmas, occur on Sundays, they are observed on the following Mondays. A change in the law passed last month, and agreed to by a coalition of retailers and unions, allows retailers to open Jan. 1 and Jan. 2, and Dec. 26, but not Dec. 25. But the wording of the change is open to interpretation. Retailers and some legislators said they thought it meant stores could be open during usual weekday hours. Other said they thought it meant Sunday hours would apply.
