<FIRST>r f PM-EditorialLibel     12-15 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Editorial Libel,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Dismisses Libel Verdict Against Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today threw out a $ 200,000 libel verdict stemming from a 1980 editorial in the <LOCATION> Belleville </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION> -RRB- News-Democrat that said a county board chairman lied about his stand on a tax increase. Without written dissent, the justices said the editorial attacking then-St. <ORGANIZATION> Clair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> was false and libelous, but that <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>'s lawyer did n't prove the newspaper's editors had reason to believe it was false when they published it As a result, the high court said, <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> failed to meet the `` actual malice'' test for libel claims by public officials _ that the statement was made with the knowledge that it was false or a `` reckless disregard'' for the truth. `` Failure to investigate does not itself establish actual malice if the -LRB- editors -RRB- did not seriously doubt the truth of their assertions,'' Justice <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> wrote in the court's opinion. Costello, who was elected this fall to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>, filed the lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the newspaper, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hargraves </PERSON>, the editorial-page editor who wrote the editorial. The case gained national attention in 1984 when <PERSON> Hargraves </PERSON> was jailed briefly for refusing to reveal the names of people he said were confidential sources for the editorial. The newspaper endorsed Costello in his 1980 campaign for county board chairman, saying he had promised to vigrously oppose any new taxes without approval by voter referendum. After the election, the county board approved a creation of a mass transit district with taxing powers, and the newspaper blasted Costello in a scathing editorial. `` <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON> lied to us ... and when he lied to us, he lied to you,'' the editorial said in part. Costello filed a libel lawsuit against the newspaper, claiming that he had lobbied against the measure but as the board's presiding officer was barred by law from speaking or voting on the issue when a roll call was taken. The lawsuit initially was dismissed by a circuit judge, but a trial was ordered by a state appellate court. Costello was awarded $ 600,000 in punitive damages and $ 450,000 in compensatory damages after the trial judge found that the editorial's statements were false and malicious. On appeal, a divided <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appellate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> panel upheld the verdict for Costello but threw out the punitive damage award and reduce the compensatory award to $ 200,000. The majority opinion called the editorial `` unduly harsh and vicious.'' However, dissenting appellate Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Steigmann </PERSON> wrote that the majority decision `` constitutes a threat to one of our most important freedoms _ the freedom of the press to criticize vigorously, and even unpleasantly, public officials in the execution of their official duties.''
</TEXT>
