<HEAD>Bundesbank Hikes Lombard Rate By A Half Percentage Point</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede, ADDS 1 graf to UPDATE with Poehl saying German hike
not part of concerted rate move.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank boosted a key interest rate 0.5 percentage points to help prevent inflation from flaring up, but a top official said the move should n't be considered part of a coordinated international rate hike. The <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> raised the Lombard lending rate to 5.5 percent from 5 percent effective Friday, but it kept the discount rate unchanged at 3.5 percent. The Lombard rate is what the central bank charges on loans to commercial banks when securities are used as collateral. The discount rate is the main commercial bank loan. <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> officials said the change in the Lombard rate came in response to concerns about rising inflation. `` We are in an environment of slightly rising interest rates,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>. He said the economy is in a process `` which one can call a boom,'' and that a tighter monetary policy is appropriate. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> also referred to interest rate developments in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and other European countries. But he stressed that the Lombard rate hike should not be seen as a concerted interest rate increase.
