<FIRST>u f AM-IBM-EEC Bjt   12-15 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-EEC, Bjt,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Decides To Extend Antitrust Settlement With EEC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it decided to extend a 1984 antitrust settlement that requires the computer giant to give certain technical information to competitors in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the accord `` has come to serve as an effective vehicle'' for resolving questions on how competing machines can be hooked up to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> equipment. The 1984 settlement suspended a 4-year antitrust case brought by the 12-nation trading bloc against <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> was allowed under the agreement the right to give, starting Jan. 1, a year's notice that it would end the arrangement. That meant the arrangement could have expired as early as Jan. 1, 1990. The agreement makes it easier for other companies to compete with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> by setting out a time schedule for release of certain data, generally within four months, to enable competing equipment to interconnect with hardware and software for <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s large-scale System 370 mainframe computers. By extending the agreement, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> avoided an uproar among Europeans who dislike the dominance of an American-based company in the European computer market. The agreement is relatively painless to <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and has not cut into its share of the market. The statement said the community and the company decided that `` neither foresees any change in circumstances that would cause <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'' to use its termination right. `` However, should such circumstances arise, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to review the matter with the -LRB- EEC -RRB- prior to giving any notice,'' the statement said. <PERSON> Jean-Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Verstrynge </PERSON>, an official in the community's competition department, said, `` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and the -LRB- EEC -RRB- have agreed that they do not foresee that at the present time such special circumstances will occur. The special conditions were not specified. The move to extend the agreement, he said, was prompted by concern the computer market would suffer from `` fear, uncertainty and doubt'' if <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> had the power to give notice at any time. `` It was to eliminate this uncertainy'' that the extension was sought, he told reporters. <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> is, in terms of revenue, the largest computer vendor in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as well as worldwide. <PERSON> Verstrynge </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s competition chief, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON>, met on Dec. 1 with <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Europe </ORGANIZATION>, to discuss a continuation of the accord. `` It was an easy meeting,'' <PERSON> Verstrynge </PERSON> said. `` But Mr. <PERSON> Sutherland </PERSON> was totally determined.'' The trading bloc will continue reviewing the agreement annually, he said. An <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, who demanded anonymity, said the arrangement `` does achieve the intended objective'' of providing a means through which the company can provide data to competitors. He said that from August 1984 to last June 30, the computer firm received 66 requests from 20 competitors covering 703 questions. <PERSON> Verstrynge </PERSON> said prior to the agreement, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> could announce a new piece of equipment without releasing technical details. `` The competitors could not react with competing products or services because they did n't have the technical information,'' he said.
</TEXT>
