<HEAD>Ex-NY Fed Reserve Bank Director Pleads Innocent To Insider Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former bank president accused of leaking confidential interest rate data while he was a director of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> pleaded innocent Thursday to insider trading charges. Robert A. Rough was arraigned before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> one week after being indicted by a federal grand jury here. Rough was accused of leaking information on the discount rate set by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to principals at <LOCATION> Bevill </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bresler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Schulman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Livingston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> brokerage firm that later collapsed. The government alleged that <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> made millions of dollars and avoided millions in losses because of the information, which Rough allegedly exchanged for $ 47,000 in interest-free loans. Rough's attorney, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON>, said he would need time to review thousands of transactions by the firm, which collapsed in April 1985. Debevoise on Thursday set Rough's bail at a $ 150,000 personal recognizance bond. A hearing on pre-trial motions was set for Feb. 14, and trial was scheduled for Feb. 21. After Thursday's hearing, <PERSON> Himmel </PERSON> and Rough declined to comment. Authorities have called Rough's case the first insider trading involving government securities and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> system. The indictment said that while he was president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Branchville </LOCATION> and sat on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s board from 1982 to 1984, Rough regularly leaked word on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s discount rate recommendation to the national <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s final determination on the rate Changes in the discount rate _ the interest on <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> loans to commercial banks _ have a powerful impact on the securities markets. <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> officials have called action involving the rate one of their most closely guarded secrets. Discount rate changes widely are regarded as the strongest indication the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> makes of the direction it wants to push interest rates, which affect the price of debt securities such as bonds. After the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> learned of the allegations against Rough, which first were mentioned in April 1987 during testimony of a criminal trial stemming from the <PERSON> Bevill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bresler </PERSON> collapse, it tightened procedures regarding the rate. Rough formally was charged with conspiracy to commit wire and securities fraud, two counts of bank fraud, one count each of wire fraud and securities fraud and two counts of making false statements to banks. Rough resigned from <ORGANIZATION> Sussex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year, prosecutors said.
