<FIRST>u f AM-ChristmasTrees Bjt   12-15 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christmas Trees, Bjt,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tree Growers Wage Christmas War Against Plastic Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSLEY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Snow falls silently on the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> battlefield as <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmuckal </PERSON> inspects the ranks of Christmas tree soldiers. Scotch pine, blue spruce and <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> fir are destined for all points of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to meet their artificial foe: the plastic Christmas tree. `` I'm worried about that,'' says the 18-year-old Schmuckal, shaking the snow from his brown hair. `` They're saying that 42 percent, 48 percent, of people are buying artificial trees,'' he said. With a year of college under his belt, Schmuckal is n't sure there is enough future in his father's northwestern <LOCATION> Lower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> Christmas tree farm for him to take the same trade. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> expects Americans will buy 34.1 million natural trees this holiday, while about 30 million people will put up artificial ones. There are other problems. The summer drought killed 2,000 young trees at the Schmuckal farm, flooding hurt <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>'s 1986 harvest, and an increase in small-scale growers threatens to undercut the market. But growers say those woes are sideline skirmishes. From the hand-worked 400 acres at the <ORGANIZATION> Schmuckal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> in northern <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> to the helicopter-harvested operations of the nation's largest Christmas tree growers, it is fake trees that are hurting a $ 1 billion-a-year business the most The market share for artificial trees has continued increasing despite a 21.8 percent jump in natural tree sales the past 11 years. Only 20 years ago, fewer than 20 percent of the holiday trees were artificial. `` We ca n't ship artificial trees fast enough,'' said <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` The trees are looking more like real trees each year. And increased prices do n't make any difference. They still sell.'' Artificial trees offer durability, safety and variety, their sponsors say. They come in metallic pink, shimmering silver or decorated with feathers. They come in symmetrical green perfection. But, `` they do n't smell Christmas. ... And they're expensive,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Brand </PERSON>, executive secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Artificial trees also are causing problems for others: a charity lot in <LOCATION> Saginaw </LOCATION> that once sold about 2,000 trees to raise money for <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> now reports sales of 1,400. Individual tree growers are doing what they can to compete, pushing quality control programs and improving tree strains. Most trees are stained green before cutting to give them a good color. Farms like the Schmuckal operation prune the crop into classic cones by hand, while some bigger operations airlift the harvest by helicopter so the trees wo n't lose needles from being dragged on the ground or hauled in a truck. But the biggest push came just this year, when the Milwaukee-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> declared war against fake trees with a $ 1 million promotional campaign. About three-fourths of the money is committed to television commercials featuring <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> weatherman <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> extolling pine needles over plastic. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, which supplied this year's Capitol Hill Christmas tree, has inaugurated its own promotion with a quality control program. Select trees that meet specifications are bestowed with a `` <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Snowfresh'' tag before being loaded onto trucks headed for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. `` We're trying to build up <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. There's something about <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. We have the soils,'' <PERSON> Brand </PERSON> said. Oregon growers would disagree, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tree </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said. Both states ship out about 6 million trees a year and claim to lead the nation. `` We do n't get into it and just say the two states are the top producers,'' <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said. Back on his father's farm, <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmuckal </PERSON> is n't certain <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> can do for Christmas trees what <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> did for potatoes. Too few trees bear the tag and the bulk of what consumers find in hometown parking lots show no origin at all. The national association is not concerned that programs such as `` Snowfresh'' have that impact. Any cut tree is desirable, <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> said. `` Just get out there and get one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
