<HEAD>Business Failures Fell 6.3 Percent in First Nine Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business failures fell by 6.3 percent during the first three quarters of this year, the best performance in nearly a decade, according to a private survey released Thursday. The number of business failures fell to 44,793 from 47,794 in the first nine months of 1987, the report by <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> stated. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION>'s corporate economist, said the decline was `` larely attributable to decreases in the levels of failures in the oil and agricultural states.'' Agricultural business failures fell 54.9 percent. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said the number of agricultural failures soared in 1987 when farmers took advantage of new protections under the federal bankruptcy law. The rush to benefit from the new provisions subsided this year, leading to the drop in failures in that industry. The only industry to see an increase in failures was wholesale trade, where 5.4 percent more companies failed during the first nine months of this year than in the same period a year earlier. In other industries, mining failures fell 25.5 percent; transportation and utility failures were off 7.8 percent; retail failures were off 6.6 percent; financial, insurance and real estate failures fell 3.4 percent; failures of service companies were down 1.8 percent; construction failures were off 1.4 percent; and manufacturing failures were essentially unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Dun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Bradstreet </ORGANIZATION> is a financial information publisher.
</TEXT>
