<SECOND>BC-EEC-Japan Dairy,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC To Hold Talks With Japan On Dairy Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will hold talks next month with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in an effort to open <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s dairy market to more imports. The 12-nation trading bloc would like <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to ease measures that it says protect the local dairy industry from foreign competition. The Japanese market for table cheese amounts to about 120,000 metric tons a year, with imports from the European trading group accounting for some 27,000 tons. The study found that sales of European dairy products in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> were hindered by import quotas on cream, butter, powdered whey, and condensed and powdered milk. It also said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> maintains a 35 percent tariff on processed and natural cheeses and limits the opening of large supermarkets that are the main outlets for sales of imported cheese. Moreover, it said, exporters were faced with long delays at customs offices and discriminatory labeling rules. As a result, European Community officials should press <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to slash the tariff on imported cheese, ease restrictions on expansion of supermarkets and shift government subsidies from production to promotion and consumer education, the study indicated. The study found that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s per capita consumption of dairy products is one of the lowest among industrialized nations.
</TEXT>
