 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Semiconductor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday announced a $ 25.2 million net loss during its second fiscal quarter and company officials blamed the loss on a sharp decline in bookings and sales and a weak semiconductor market. The results contrasted sharply with those of another chip maker, <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which said late Wednesday the profits in its first fiscal quarter nearly quadrupled. National Semiconductor of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clara </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said its loss was in contrast to a net profit of $ 11.6 million, or 8 cents a share, a year earlier. Analysts were expecting the losses, noting that the company faced a squeeze on pricing because of intense competition in its markets. Sales for the second quarter, which ended Nov. 27, were $ 705.3 million compared to $ 640 million for the same quarter last year. For the first half of fiscal year 1989, sales were $ 1.35 billion, with a net loss of $ 55.7 million. Sales in the same period of 1988 were $ 1.15 billion with net earnings of $ 25.1 million or 19 cents per share. <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Boise </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, did better because it makes computer memory chips, which are priced highly because of short supplies. It earned $ 32.2 million on revenue of $ 110.4 million during the quarter that ended Dec. 1. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 8.4 million on revenue of $ 43.2 million. Per-share earnings were 88 cents for the quarter, compared to 33 cents per share a year ago. However, both income and revenue were down from the last quarter of <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 fiscal year, when the company had a record quarterly profit. The declines were due largely to a higher effective tax rate and costs associated with hiring new employees, said <PERSON> Kipp </PERSON> <PERSON> Bedard </PERSON>, manager of investor relations. In addition, the company has been setting money for legal expenses. In November, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> filed a patent infringement lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION> alleges that <ORGANIZATION> Micron </ORGANIZATION> is producing memory chips that disregard TI's patents.
