<HEAD>Mobil Ends Use Of Ozone-Depleting Substance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it has stopped using ozone-destroying chemicals to make its foam packaging for food, following through on a commitment made in April. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> is a leading producer of foam food containers for schools, hospitals and fast-food restaurants. A plant in <LOCATION> Bakersfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, made most of the foam that used the chemicals, called chlorofluorocarbons. The voluntary elimination of the compounds will affect less than 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s polystyrene foam products business, the company said. `` We're able to take this step because our research effort gave us an alternate blowing agent that is environmentally acceptable,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Y </PERSON>. Glass, vice president and general manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Polystyrene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Chlorofluorocarbons are believed responsible for depleting the earth's ozone layer, a protective shield that screens out harmful ultraviolet rays from the sun. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Packaging </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> announced on April 12 a voluntary program by all its members to phase out use of chlorofluorocarbons by the end of 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, recently announced it was opening a plastic foam recycling plant in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to recycle polystyrene foam products and plastic cutlery.
