 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> signed a letter of intent to purchase <ORGANIZATION> Hercules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s olefin carpet fiber business, doubling its share of the international market for the cheap commercial carpet fibers, a <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> spokesman announced Thursday. The purchase price was not disclosed, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> McAndrews </PERSON>, director of the flooring systems division. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> accounted for about $ 2 billion of the $ 20 billion commercial and residential carpet market sales in 1988, <PERSON> McAndrews </PERSON> said. The acquisition of the Hercules business, reported to sell $ 50 million to $ 60 million annually, will expand <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the $ 400 million olefin fiber market to more than $ 100 million, <PERSON> McAndrews </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> announced last month it planned to begin making olefin fibers as part of a new program to market commercial carpets sold through retail outlets. Under a supply cotract, <PERSON> Hercules </PERSON> will continue producing olefine carpet fibers at near capacity for three to five years, according to a company statement. <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> will have exclusive rights to that production, after which time it plans to have expanded its capacity, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> also will obtain rights to <PERSON> Hercules </PERSON>' customer list and marketing information, the company said. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> is a diversified chemical, specialty products and energy company with 1987 sales of $ 30.5 billion.
