<HEAD>Platinum Market Collapses On Ford News</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Platinum futures prices collapsed Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> announced development of a platinum-free catalytic converter that could slash global demand for the metal by one-third. On other markets, sugar futures plunged; energy futures fell; grain futures were higher; soybeans were lower; livestock and meat were mixed; and stock-index futures retreated. All platinum futures except the spot December contract settled down the daily limit of $ 25 with the January contract at $ 579.50 a troy ounce. The spot contract, which has no limit, finished $ 34.10 lower at $ 531.90. The use of platinum as a catalyst for chemical reactions in automobile pollution-control systems accounted for about 38 percent of world consumption of newly produced platinum last year and was expected to represent about 35 percent of consumption this year. Speculative buying of platinum futures had been rising due to recent projections that demand would continue outstripping production through 1992. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement jolted the market. `` It's a disaster,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` All our reasons for being bullish on platinum have been defused.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Demler </PERSON>, New York-based metals economist with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> agreed: `` It's a major development. It could potentially wipe out one-third of platinum consumption.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> announced a pilot program for the invention Wednesday evening but the news did n't hit the markets until after the opening of platinum trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>. `` It came in dribs and drabs,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>. `` I had heard it as a rumor as soon as the market opened but I was hesitant to act.'' She said the market started falling from its $ 606 opening, ad at $ 601 she recommended selling the contract. That was at about 9:35 a.m., she said. Selling quickly escalated until the market went limit-down at about 9:50 a.m. The first news service report of <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>'s remarks came across the wires at about 10 a.m. EST. The platinum selloff spread to gold and silver futures, which are traded on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled $ 8.60 to $ 10.10 lower with February at $ 416.60 a troy ounce; silver was 11.6 cents to 13 cents lower with March at $ 6.185 a troy ounce. Sugar futures prices plummeted on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on indications that near-term availability of sugar was on the rise, analysts said. Bearish factors included <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s announcement that it planned to move up shipments of 100,000 metric tons of sugar from July to March, and indications that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had been selling sugar, said <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganes </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Sugar settled .44 cents to 2.76 cents lower with the active March contract at 10.84 cents a pound. Oil futures retreated in quiet trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid profit-taking following the previous session's rally, analysts said. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 38 cents lower with January at $ 16.35 a barrel; heating oil was .19 cent to .55 cent lower with January at 50.94 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .05 cent to .32 cent lower with January at 43.65 cents a gallon. Grain futures finished modestly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> may have purchased up to 2 million metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn. Soybean futures declined on the lack of confirmation of a rumored sale of soybean meal to the Soviets, analysts said. Wheat settled 1 -RCB- cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 4.28 -LCB- a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.68 \ a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 2 -LCB- cents higher with December at $ 2.14 a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 3 cents lower with January at $ 7.75 -LCB- a bushel Cattle futures finished mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in positioning ahead of Friday's monthly cattle-on-feed report from the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, while most pork futures declined. Live cattle settled .02 cent lower to .37 cent higher with December at 72.97 cents a pound; fe