<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> signed a four-year maritime agreement Thursday that will ensure access of each nation's vessels to the ports of the other The two nations also pledged their intention to provide for the sharing of cargo carriage in two-way trade, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> announcement said. Vessels of each nation would be assured of at least a third of all such cargoes, it said. Under the agreement, U.S.-flag vessels may enter 40 Chinese ports upon 24 hours advance notice, and Chinese vessels will have the same access to all but 12 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ports. `` This agreement, which caps a five-year effort to improve U.S.-China maritime relations, will provide new opportunities for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers serving <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON>. Signing for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was Minister of Communications <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Yongchang </PERSON>. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Sea-Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced it will open shipping offices in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tainjin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dalian </LOCATION>.
