naissance, the indictment said. It said they used several means to siphon off funds from the offering, including making checks payable to accounts under different names controlled by <PERSON> Wynn </PERSON> and under his wife's maiden name. They allegedly used $ 18,500 to buy personal jewelry. Phony loans were made to companies created by the defendants, the indictment said. The defendants could not be reached for comment. The Wynns have an unpublished telephone number and <PERSON> LaMagra </PERSON> had no listing in <LOCATION> Paramus </LOCATION>. `` Mr. <PERSON> LaMagra </PERSON> just unequivocably denies any criminal wrongdoing in any of these matters,'' said his attorney, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Groot </PERSON>. He said the government had strung together innocent business activities to create a fiction of wrongdoing. <PERSON> LaMagra </PERSON> has a `` history of working in the banking industry'' and is a well-known business consultant, the lawyer said. An attorney for the Wynns, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> A. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, could not be reached. He did not return a phone message. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, chief of the frauds division, said the lag in unsealing the indictment was because of a continuing investigation. <PERSON> LaMagra </PERSON> was convicted in federal court in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, in April for conspiring to prepare false income tax returns for a reputed captain in the <PERSON> Bonanno </PERSON> crime family, <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Attanasio </PERSON>, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordenbrook </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>. That case is on appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> charged penny-stock underwriter Monarch, which maintains its innocence, with illegally inflating the stock in 1982 and 1983 of <ORGANIZATION> Toxic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Containment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a hazardous waste cleanup company, and <ORGANIZATION> Liquidation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a business consulting firm for distressed companies. In November 1987, a former Wall Street analyst was sentenced to eight years in prison by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION> for writing falsely positive reports on the companies while having a financial interest in them. Thursday's indictment said the Wynns and <PERSON> LaMagra </PERSON>, through false claims and a false prospectus, caused Monarch to make `` false representations to induce the public to invest'' in Renaissance. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said the defendants face at least 50 years in jail each if convicted of all the charges. They were not arrested and no court appearance was set.
