<HEAD>GE, Two Employees Plead Innocent to Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and two employees pleaded innocent Thursday to federal charges of padding the cost of a battlefield computer system by $ 10 million. GE, the nation's third-largest defense contractor, and the two employees are charged with hiding savings negotiated with subcontractors in a $ 270 million Army contract to make the computer system. The two employees are <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> of King of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> `` The government alleges in essence that their materials and subcontractor costs were inflated and the defendants and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> knew it,'' said <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harbist </PERSON>, the assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney prosecuting the case. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, said the company would stand by the statement it released at the time of the indictments. In that statement, the company labeled the charges `` unfair and unfounded.'' The company also said that an internal investigation into the same matter showed pricing discrepancies totaling $ 3.69 million, which the company already has refunded. In May 1985, GE pleaded guilty to unrelated contract-fraud charges, paying a $ 1.04 million fine and reimbursing the government $ 800,000. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Undercofler </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, the lawyer representing GE, said the innocent pleas were entered in a brief hearing before federal magistrate <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Naythons </PERSON>. A trial date for the current charges was set for Feb. 13. <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> were released on their own recognizance under a $ 250,000 bond. As part of the release agreement, the two men surrendered their passports and agreed to restrict their travel to the eastern district of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Harbist </PERSON> said. The 321-count indictment, released Nov. 29, charges that the scheme was conducted through <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION>'s wholly-owned subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, or <LOCATION> MATSCO </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> suburb of King of <LOCATION> Prussia </LOCATION>. GE was awarded a $ 250 million contract in June 1983 to make the `` decentralized automated service support system,'' called the DAS-3, for the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. According to the indictment, the company and the two employees lied to the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> about the prices <ORGANIZATION> GE </ORGANIZATION> was paying for parts and raw materials and double-billed for some materials. The Army would have been defrauded of $ 22 million if the scheme had not been uncovered, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said. The government charges <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON>, 41, formerly the subsidiary's subcontracts manager, with trying to cover up the scheme by altering dates of purchase orders and withholding information from goverment auditors <PERSON> Leo </PERSON>, 51, formerly the materials manager for <LOCATION> MATSCO </LOCATION>, is also charged with lying to a federal auditor. Both men have been transferred to other parts of GE. <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> faces a maximum of 55 years in prison and $ 1.3 million in fines if he is convicted on one count of racketeering, five counts of mail fraud and two counts of making false statements and concealing material facts from a federal agency. <PERSON> Badolato </PERSON> faces the same penalties plus $ 5,000 more in fines if convicted of one count of racketeering, five counts of mail fraud, one count of obstructing agency proceedings and one count of making false statements and concealing material facts from a federal agency. GE is charged with five counts of mail fraud and 312 counts of presenting false claims to the government. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Flood </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said he was unaware of any proceedings to suspend or bar GE from bidding on defense contracts. An Army spokesman did not return calls about the matter. <PERSON> Jamison </PERSON> would not comment on the topic.
