<HEAD>ConAgra's Profit Up 17 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday said its earnings rose 17 percent in the second quarter and were up 21 percent for the first half of fiscal 1989, propelled by strength in poultry and prepared foods businesses. The food processing conglomerate said second-quarter earnings were a record $ 87.4 million, or 71 cents a share, on sales of $ 2.81 billion. That compares with earnings of $ 74.5 million, or 61 cents a share, on sales of $ 2.30 billion in last year's second quarter. For the first half, earnings were $ 145.5 million, or $ 1.19 a share, on sales of $ 5.58 billion. That compares with earnings of $ 120.2 million, or 98 cents a share, on sales of $ 4.71 billion in the same period last year. The company said its prepared foods segment had a substantial profit gain in the second quarter and first half, led by an increase in poultry earnings. Other strong performers were turkey products, consumer frozen foods, agricultural products and grain processing and trading units. Fresh red meat earnings were below last year's levels, but losses in the Armour processed meat unit narrowed in the first half, the company said. `` Record second-quarter and first-half results are particularly satisfying in light of the tough business environment,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ConAgra </ORGANIZATION> chairman and chief executive officer. `` In addition to intense competition, our businesses were challenged by higher and volitile ingredient costs caused by the drought,'' he said.
