<FIRST>u f AM-TakeoverBill     12-15 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Takeover Bill,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Bill Advances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> voted unanimously Thursday to temporarily restore to corporations in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> a weapon to fight hostile takeover attempts by other companies. The measure validating the use of so-called `` poison pills'' was approved 129-0 by the state <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and 52-0 by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and sent to Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>'s desk. The legislation, a product of negotiations involving the governor's office, is expected to quickly be signed into law by <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. The measure is designed to undo until April 1, 1989, the result of a state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling earlier this year in which a poison pill that <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> tried to use to fend off a hostile takeover by <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> was ruled illegal. That court decided <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state laws prohibit the inequitable treatment of shareholders. That cleared the way for <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition and raised concerns among the more than 100 companies in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that have poison pill rules in place as protection against hostile suitors. Under the poison pill scenario, a target company gives shareholders the right to buy additional stock at reduced prices when an outside party buys up a certain percentage of the company's shares That makes it far more expensive for a suitor to buy enough stock to get a controlling interest in the target company. The poison pill is designed chiefly to give a company time to fend off an unfriendly takeover, if it chooses, or to negotiate a better price for its shareholders if it goes along with a buyout offer. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sponsor of the bill, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Schermerhorn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Orange </LOCATION>, said the Republican-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> originally favored validating the poison pills for 18 months, but he said that time period was reduced due to opposition in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. A special task force made up of business leaders and others is in charge of studying the use of poison pills and other aspects of the merger and acquisition field and will report to the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> by early spring. Schermerhorn said he'd been told there were `` billions of dollars out there'' that could be used in acquisitions and that some effort must be made to head off the wholesale buying and selling of companies. State. Sen. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Leichter </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Democrat who voted for the measure, said poison pills are sometimes used by corporate management to `` keep itself in control.'' He said that can lead to what he called abuses. `` Poison pills really are a way of changing the rules in the middle of a game,'' he said.
</TEXT>
