<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules Leasing Violated Antitrust Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court on Thursday ruled that the leasing of two corn wet milling plants in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Archer-Daniels-Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 was a violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act. The government had claimed in a suit filed in December 1982 that the lease created an unreasonable restraint of trade because it would give <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> a large enough share of the high fructose corn syrup -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- market to control the price of the product. In the early 1970s, new technology allowed the processing by wet corn milling plants of certain corn syrups into a substitute for sugar in sweetening various products, including canned fruits and soft drinks. The suit noted that since 1934 sugar cane and beet sugar growers have benefitted from either direct subsidies or sugar price supports enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Because of the price supports, the price of <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> has been substantially lower than the price of sugar for many years. The government presented evidence that if the lease between <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Nabisco </PERSON> was consummated, <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> would be able, because of its newly established market position, to raise the price of <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> to a level just below the price of sugar. The companies, however, were granted a summary judgment in the case in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. That court agreed that sugar and <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> are in the same relevant product market, and that <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION>'s share of that market was not sufficient to constitute a violation of the Sherman Act or the Clayton Act In its 2-1 decision Thursday, a panel of the 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled, however, that while sugar and <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> are functionally interchangeable, they are not reasonably interchangeable because of the price differential between the two products and therefore are not in the same relevant product market. The majority on the appeals court panel comprised judges <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillian </PERSON>. Dissenting was Judge <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, who said he agreed with the district court's decision that <ORGANIZATION> HFCS </ORGANIZATION> and sugar belong in the same relevant product market.
</TEXT>
