<HEAD>Coors Employees Reject Teamsters Representation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Brewery workers at <ORGANIZATION> Adolph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have voted overwhelmingly against union representation by the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>, a spokeswoman for the brewery said Thursday night. Results of the two days of balloting on union representation were announced by <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Crider </PERSON>, a brewery spokeswoman. `` Of the 1,562 eligible workers at the brewery, 1,081 voted against union representation, while 413 voted for the union,'' she said. `` Brewery workers have decided that they do n't want union representation,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Meadows </PERSON>, director of community relations for <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>. `` Coors will continue to work to maintain high-quality relationships among its work force without third-party representation.'' The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> switched a live telephone in Golden to a recording after the vote was announced. The vote followed 18 months of union and company politicking at the brewery, the nation's fourth largest. The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> needed a simple majority to win representation for the 1,600 Coors brewery workers. The brewery has been non-union since December 1978, when workers voted overwhelmingly to withdraw from the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> after a bitter 20-month strike. The strike had been effectively broken and triggered a nationwide organized labor boycott of Coors products. That boycott officially ended in August 1987 with an agreement between Coors and the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> and including the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>. An agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> stipulated that win or lose, there will be no return to the boycott against Coors products. Voting began Wednesday, when 126 brewery workers who had Thursday off voted. It continued at three locations at the brewery on Thursday, said Meadows. Key issues in the election included wages and pensions. The Teamsters have touted the wages recently implemented and the pension plan under consideration by <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s new brewery in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Collins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>. Coors officials have warned employees not to count on those wage and pension levels even if the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> win, saying <PERSON> Busch </PERSON> is four times as large as <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> and can afford salaries and benefits that <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> can not <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Coors </PERSON>, addressing workers Monday in a series of meetings at the brewery, rejected the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' claims that a union victory would boost sales at <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION>, which last year shipped 15.6 million barrels of beer and expects to sell 17 million barrels this year. Teamsters Brewery Division Chief <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Laughton </PERSON> has said the union label would make Coors more palatable to many consumers and boost sales as much as 10 percent. But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, a beer industry analyst in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, said the vote wo n't affect Coors sales one way or another. `` A non-union workforce is going to cost the company some business. Similarly, a union workforce could cost some sales. The question is: Is it a significant amount of business?'' he asked. The election was being conducted independently of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> Prof. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON>, an experienced labor arbitrator, was acting as the independent monitor. <ORGANIZATION> Coors </ORGANIZATION> reported third-quarter beer shipments of 5.57 million barrels, up 8.1 percent from the same period a year earlier, and net earnings for the period of $ 21.64 million, up marginally from a year earlier.
